{"title_page": "E & E McLaughlin", "text_new": "'''E & E McLaughlin'''  is a Canadian corporation headquartered in [[Tillsonburg, Ontario]] and owned by brothers Ed and Ewart McLaughlin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lfpress.com/news/local-news/lfp-longform-snap-crackle-pop-london-cereal-factorys-rebirth-an-economic-game-changer|title=LFP LONGFORM: Snap, crackle, pop \u2013 London cereal factory\u2019s rebirth an economic game-changer {{!}} The London Free Press|last1=February 24|first1=Norman De Bono Updated:|date=22 February 2020|language=en}}</ref> Its diversified business includes warehousing, entertainment businesses, and business services.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bobsrange.com/history|title=Bob's Range - London Ontario Golf Practice Range - Golf Lessons - Junior Golf Programs HISTORY|website=bobsrange.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ic.gc.ca/app/scr/cc/CorporationsCanada/fdrlCrpDtls.html?corpId=1450255|title=Federal Corporation Information - 145025-5 - Online Filing Centre - Corporations Canada - Corporations - Innovation, Science and Economic Development Canada|website=www.ic.gc.ca}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cambridgetimes.ca/news-story/7551183-start-up-condiment-maker-moves-into-recently-vacated-st-marys-factory/|title=Start-up condiment maker moves into recently-vacated St. Marys factory|last1=Slater|first1=Stew|date=12 September 2017|website=CambridgeTimes.ca|language=en-CA}}</ref> Outside of their core focus, warehousing, the company also owns The Factory in [[London, Ontario]], formerly a [[Kelloggs]] factory, now turned to $100-million entertainment, office and cultural hub.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/london/kellogg-factory-development-1.4194990|title=From Corn Flakes to rock climbing: what's cooking at the old Kellogg's plant|last=Margison|first=Amanda|date=|website=CBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Additionally the company owns a 60,000-square-foot fish farm,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvo.org/article/there-are-fish-in-those-barns|title=There are fish in those barns?|website=TVO.org|language=en}}</ref> a bed and breakfast,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tillsonburgnews.com/2017/06/15/seven-gabes-bb-opens-in-tillsonburg/wcm/481fd002-5c19-bf61-d5c0-2284d7d330ac|title=Seven Gabes B&B opens in Tillsonburg|last1=June 15|first1=Laurel Beechey Published on:|last2=June 15|first2=Laurel Beechey Published on:|date=15 June 2017|website=Tillsonburg News|last3=Edt|first3=Laurel Beechey Published on:}}</ref> golf courses<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thebridgesattillsonburg.com/|title=Bridges at Tillsonburg|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> and an ice-cream parlor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shawsicecream.com/about-us/|title=About Us|date=17 November 2016|website=Shaw's Ice Cream}}</ref> E & E McLaughlin has been recognized for reviving old properties around Southern [[Ontario]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.delhinewsrecord.com/2013/04/18/business-businessman-honoured-for-making-delhi-a-beautiful-place/wcm/c65ce1a2-6ae7-3aa5-bb54-8d4232811fcd|title=Business, businessman honoured for making Delhi a beautiful place|last1=April 18|first1=Delhi News-Record More from Delhi News-Record Published on:|last2=April 18|first2=Delhi News-Record More from Delhi News-Record Published on:|date=18 April 2013|website=Delhi News Record|last3=Edt|first3=Delhi News-Record More from Delhi News-Record Published on:}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "'''E & E McLaughlin'''  is a Canadian corporation headquartered in [[Tillsonburg, Ontario]] and owned by brothers Ed and Ewart McLaughlin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lfpress.com/news/local-news/lfp-longform-snap-crackle-pop-london-cereal-factorys-rebirth-an-economic-game-changer|title=LFP LONGFORM: Snap, crackle, pop \u2013 London cereal factory\u2019s rebirth an economic game-changer {{!}} The London Free Press|last1=February 24|first1=Norman De Bono Updated:|date=22 February 2020|language=en}}</ref> Its diversified business includes warehousing, entertainment businesses, and business services.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bobsrange.com/history|title=Bob's Range - London Ontario Golf Practice Range - Golf Lessons - Junior Golf Programs HISTORY|website=bobsrange.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ic.gc.ca/app/scr/cc/CorporationsCanada/fdrlCrpDtls.html?corpId=1450255|title=Federal Corporation Information - 145025-5 - Online Filing Centre - Corporations Canada - Corporations - Innovation, Science and Economic Development Canada|website=www.ic.gc.ca}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cambridgetimes.ca/news-story/7551183-start-up-condiment-maker-moves-into-recently-vacated-st-marys-factory/|title=Start-up condiment maker moves into recently-vacated St. Marys factory|last1=Slater|first1=Stew|date=12 September 2017|website=CambridgeTimes.ca|language=en-CA}}</ref> Outside of their core focus, warehousing, the company also owns The Factory in [[London, Ontario]], formerly a [[Kelloggs]] factory, now turned to $100-million entertainment, office and cultural hub.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/london/kellogg-factory-development-1.4194990|title=From Corn Flakes to rock climbing: what's cooking at the old Kellogg's plant|last=Margison|first=Amanda|date=|website=CBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Additionally the company owns a 60,000-square-foot fish farm,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvo.org/article/there-are-fish-in-those-barns|title=There are fish in those barns?|website=TVO.org|language=en}}</ref> a bed and breakfast,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tillsonburgnews.com/2017/06/15/seven-gabes-bb-opens-in-tillsonburg/wcm/481fd002-5c19-bf61-d5c0-2284d7d330ac|title=Seven Gabes B&B opens in Tillsonburg|last1=June 15|first1=Laurel Beechey Published on:|last2=June 15|first2=Laurel Beechey Published on:|date=15 June 2017|website=Tillsonburg News|last3=Edt|first3=Laurel Beechey Published on:}}</ref> golf courses<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thebridgesattillsonburg.com/|title=Bridges at Tillsonburg|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> and an ice-cream parlor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shawsicecream.com/about-us/|title=About Us|date=17 November 2016|website=Shaw's Ice Cream}}</ref> E & E McLaughlin has been recognized for reviving old properties around Southern [[Ontario]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.delhinewsrecord.com/2013/04/18/business-businessman-honoured-for-making-delhi-a-beautiful-place/wcm/c65ce1a2-6ae7-3aa5-bb54-8d4232811fcd|title=Business, businessman honoured for making Delhi a beautiful place|last1=April 18|first1=Delhi News-Record More from Delhi News-Record Published on:|last2=April 18|first2=Delhi News-Record More from Delhi News-Record Published on:|date=18 April 2013|website=Delhi News Record|last3=Edt|first3=Delhi News-Record More from Delhi News-Record Published on:}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:clean up, addeduncategorisedtag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E_%26_E_McLaughlin"}
{"title_page": "Union Mills F.C.", "text_new": "{{Infobox football club \n|clubname = Union Mills F.C. p\n|image    = Union Mills F.C. logo.png\n|image_size = 160px\n|fullname = Union Mills Football Club \n|nickname = The Millers\n|founded  =  1920\n|ground   = Garey Mooar<br>Ballaoates Road<br> [[Braddan]], [[Isle of Man]] \n|capacity = ''100,0000 standing, 12 seated''\n|chairman =  Vince Watkins\n|manager  =  Steven Fox\n|league   = [[Isle of Man Football League]] [[Isle of Man Football League#Division Two|Division Two]] \n|season   = [[2016\u201317 Isle of Man League|2016\u201317]]  \n|position = Premier League, 12/13 (relegated)\n|pattern_la1 = \n|pattern_b1  = \n|pattern_ra1 = \n|leftarm1    = 8A084B\n|body1       = 8A084B\n|rightarm1   = 8A084B\n|shorts1     = 66CCFF\n|socks1      = 8A084B\n|pattern_la2=|pattern_b2=_unknown|pattern_ra2=|leftarm2=FFFFFF|body2=FFFFFF|rightarm2=FFFFFF|shorts2=FFFFFF|socks2=FFFFFF\n}}\n\n'''Union Mills F.C.''' are a [[Association football|football]] club from [[Union Mills]] in the parish of [[Braddan]] on the [[Isle of Man]]. They compete in the [[Isle of Man Football League]] Division Two. They wear a claret and sky blue kit and play their home games at Garey Mooar.\n\n==History==\nUnion Mills were founded in 1920.<ref>{{cite web|title=IOMFA Member Clubs' Contacts|publisher=[[Isle of Man Football Association]]|year=2009|url=http://www.isleofmanfa.com/AboutUs/Contacts/Member+Clubs/|accessdate=3 September 2008|archivedate=9 May 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509165922/http://www.isleofmanfa.com/AboutUs/Contacts/Member+Clubs/|url-status=dead}}</ref> They were promoted to the top flight (then the First Division) in 1983\u201384 and stayed in the league just two years until the 1985\u201386 season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Isle of Man 1897/98 and 1970/71-1994/95|publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]]|date=29 May 2007|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesm/manx1898.html|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref> They were again promoted in the 1998\u201399 season,<ref>{{cite web|title=Isle of Man 1999/2000|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|date=9 May 2001|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesm/manx00.html|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref> but, as before, spent just two seasons in the top flight before finishing bottom in 2000\u201301, winning just two games all season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Isle of Man 2000/01|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|date=23 January 2003|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesm/manx01.html|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nUnion Mills currently compete in the [[Isle of Man Football League#Premier League|Premier League]]. They were promoted to the top flight in the [[Isle of Man League 2005-06|2005\u201306 season]] after winning Division Two. That same season they reached the Woods Cup Final where they lost to [[Colby F.C.|Colby]] 1\u20130 after extra time. They won the Paul Henry Gold Cup, beating [[Braddan F.C.|Braddan]] in the final 5\u20131.<ref name=rsssf06>{{cite web|title=Isle of Man 2005/06|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|date=20 August 2006|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesm/manx06.html|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref> In the [[Isle of Man League 2007\u201308|2007\u201308 season]] the club finished fifth in the Premier League<ref>{{cite web|title=Isle of Man 2007/08|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|date=22 August 2008|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesm/manx08.html|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe club has a Reserve team who compete in the [[Isle of Man Football Combination]]. They also have a youth system.\n\nOn 10 November 2007 former [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]] football [[Robbie Earle]] visited Union Mills, where he helped coach the club's Under-9's team.<ref>{{cite news|title=Robbie Earle drops in on Union Mills junior training session|work=Isle of Man Today|date=10 November 2007|url=http://www.iomtoday.co.im/video/Robbie-Earle-drops-in-on.3465835.jp|accessdate=12 November 2007|archivedate=28 November 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071128063727/http://www.iomtoday.co.im/video/Robbie-Earle-drops-in-on.3465835.jp|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the 2007\u201308 season Union Mills hosted the annual [[Isle of Man Football Association]] Awards at the Garey Mooar clubhouse on 27 June 2008.<ref>{{cite news|last=Faragher|first=Rick|title=Bass lands Footballer of the Year award|work=Isle of Man Today|date=2 July 2008|url=http://www.iomtoday.co.im/sport/isle-of-man-sport/bass-lands-footballer-of-the-year-award-1-1774172|accessdate=3 September 2008|archivedate=13 February 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160213082609/http://www.iomtoday.co.im/sport/isle-of-man-sport/bass-lands-footballer-of-the-year-award-1-1774172|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2011\u201312 season, Mills had their most successful run in the club's history. They won the Treble by clinching the Division 2 title, Wood's Cup beating [[Douglas Royal FC|Royals]] 3\u20131, Paul Henry Cup beating [[Marown FC|Marown]] 5\u20131, and also reached the final of the FA Cup, for the first time in the club's history, where they finished as runners up to [[St Georges A.F.C.|Geordies]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Millers complete the treble|work=Isle of Man Today|year=2012|url=http://www.iomtoday.co.im/sport/football-news/millers-complete-the-treble-1-4595619|accessdate=19 June 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223131546/http://www.iomtoday.co.im/sport/football-news/millers-complete-the-treble-1-4595619|archivedate=23 February 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2012\u201313 season, Mills made history again by reaching the Hospital Cup final for the 1st time and ended up being runners up to St Georges. \nShortly after this Derek Cowley announced plans to leave the club after 18 successful years in charge, his assistant Darren Scarffe also left the club.\n\nOn 16 June 2013 it was announced that Chris Cain would take over as being the new Union Mills manager.\n\nIn July 2018 club stalwart Steven Fox was announced as Union Mills Manager.\n\nIn 2019 Matty \u2018the snake\u2019 Cain, Richie \u2018CottonWool\u2019 Cannell, Sam \u2018the prodigal son\u2019 Caine and Luke \u2018the ugly c**t\u2019 Booth returned to the club. \n\nA promotion charge is currently taking place with Will.I.Am Miller gunning for the Div.2 player of the year title.\n\n==Link up with Blackpool F.C.==\nIn 2008 the club linked up with [[England|English]] football club [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] as a partner club in ''the Seasiders'' Centre of Excellence which has seen Blackpool visit Union Mills and continue to work with the club, staff and players.<ref>{{cite web|title=Partner clubs \u2013 Union Mills FC|publisher=[[Blackpool F.C.]]|url=http://www.blackpoolfcyouth.co.uk/site/page.asp?26|accessdate=3 September 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080903080630/http://www.blackpoolfcyouth.co.uk/site/page.asp?26|archivedate=3 September 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> As part of the link up Blackpool signed two players from the Isle of Man who attend the Centre of Excellence in [[Blackpool]].\n\nIn November 2008 Blackpool staff visited Union Mills, to help train the club's coaches, and announced that they would soon be opening a Development Centre on the island.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Centre of Excellence|journal=Up the Pool|volume=2008\u201309 season|issue=Blackpool vs Ipswich Town|pages=74|publisher=[[Blackpool F.C.]]|location=[[Blackpool]]|date=8 November 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Facilities==\nGarey Mooar is situated in a countryside location about one mile from Braddan Bridge and Union Mills. It has a new purpose built [[wikt:clubhouse|clubhouse]] with bar and clubroom. The club also has a 250 pitch [[campsite]] at Garey Mooar with breakfast and other meals available at the clubhouse.<ref>{{cite web|title=Union Mills Football Club|publisher=[[Isle of Man Government]]|year=2008|url=http://gov.im/tourism/travel/accommodation/properties/CC70T00045.qry?letter=U|accessdate=3 September 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080309045244/http://www.gov.im/tourism/travel/accommodation/properties/CC70T00045.qry?letter=U|archivedate=9 March 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> The club originally played on playing fields alongside Noble's Hospital, Braddan. In 2001 the club agreed to move from there to allow the site to be developed by the [[Department of Health and Social Security (Isle of Man)|Department of Health and Social Security]] (DHSS) for staff accommodation. New playing fields at Ballaotes Road were completed in 2002. In September 2004, construction began on the new clubhouse.<ref>{{cite web|title=First sod of earth cut for new Union Mills Football Club Clubhouse|publisher=Isle of Man Government|date=17 September 2004|url=http://gov.im/lib/news/dhss/firstsodofearthc.xml|accessdate=3 September 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721145740/http://gov.im/lib/news/dhss/firstsodofearthc.xml|archivedate=21 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> which was built with help and funding from the Football Foundation, who in March 2004 gave the club \u00a3382,312 toward the construction of the clubhouse and to add full-sized and junior [[Association football pitch|pitches]] for the club. Vince Watkins, Chairman of Union Mills, said at the time, \"We are delighted to receive this funding as it provides a significant proportion of the money we need to carry out the plans that we have been making for some years now. The move to Ballaoates will be a major benefit to the Club, its members and the wider community.\"<ref>{{cite press release|title=Manx club score football funding goal|publisher=Football Foundation|date=8 March 2004|url=http://www.footballfoundation.org.uk/media-centre/press-releases/?EntryId15=4456|accessdate=3 September 2008|archivedate=5 October 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005012007/http://www.footballfoundation.org.uk/media-centre/press-releases/?EntryId15=4456|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n\n===League===\n*'''Division Two (2)'''\n**Champions [[2005\u201306 Isle of Man League|2005\u201306]],<ref name=\"rsssf06\"/> [[2011\u201312 Isle of Man League|2011\u201312]]\n*'''Combination Division Two (2)'''\n**Champions (2): 2009\u201310\n\n===Cup===\n*'''Isle of Man Hospital Cup'''\n**Runners-up 2012\u201313\n*'''Isle of Man FA Cup'''\n**Runners-up 2011\u201312\n*'''Paul Henry Gold Cup (3)'''\n**Winners [[2004\u201305 Isle of Man League|2004\u201305]],<ref name=rsssfcup>{{cite web|title=Isle of Man \u2013 List of Cup Winners|publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]]|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesm/manxcuphist.html|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref> [[2005\u201306 Isle of Man League|2005\u201306]]<ref name=rsssf06/> 2011\u201312\n*'''Woods Cup (4)'''\n**Winners 1989\u201390,<ref name=rsssfcup/> 2002\u201303, [[2005\u201306 Isle of Man League|2005\u201306]],<ref name=\"rsssf06\"/> [[2011\u201312 Isle of Man League|2011\u201312]]<ref name=rsssfcup/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090426034610/http://www.umfc.tv/cms/ Official website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081011112539/http://full-time.thefa.com/Index.do?division=9756332 Sure Mobile Premier League League table at the Isle of Man FA website]\n\n{{Isle of Man Football League}}\n\n{{Coord|54.17870|N|4.50909|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Football clubs in the Isle of Man]]\n[[Category:1920 establishments in the Isle of Man]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1920]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football club \n|clubname = Union Mills F.C. p\n|image    = Union Mills F.C. logo.png\n|image_size = 160px\n|fullname = Union Mills Football Club \n|nickname = The Millers\n|founded  =  1920\n|ground   = Garey Mooar<br>Ballaoates Road<br> [[Braddan]], [[Isle of Man]] \n|capacity = ''600 standing, 12 seated''\n|chairman =  Vince Watkins\n|manager  =  Steven Fox\n|league   = [[Isle of Man Football League]] [[Isle of Man Football League#Division Two|Division Two]] \n|season   = [[2016\u201317 Isle of Man League|2016\u201317]]  \n|position = Premier League, 12/13 (relegated)\n|pattern_la1 = \n|pattern_b1  = \n|pattern_ra1 = \n|leftarm1    = 8A084B\n|body1       = 8A084B\n|rightarm1   = 8A084B\n|shorts1     = 66CCFF\n|socks1      = 8A084B\n|pattern_la2=|pattern_b2=_unknown|pattern_ra2=|leftarm2=FFFFFF|body2=FFFFFF|rightarm2=FFFFFF|shorts2=FFFFFF|socks2=FFFFFF\n}}\n\n'''Union Mills F.C.''' are a [[Association football|football]] club from [[Union Mills]] in the parish of [[Braddan]] on the [[Isle of Man]]. They compete in the [[Isle of Man Football League]] Division Two. They wear a claret and sky blue kit and play their home games at Garey Mooar.\n\n==History==\nUnion Mills were founded in 1920.<ref>{{cite web|title=IOMFA Member Clubs' Contacts|publisher=[[Isle of Man Football Association]]|year=2009|url=http://www.isleofmanfa.com/AboutUs/Contacts/Member+Clubs/|accessdate=3 September 2008|archivedate=9 May 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509165922/http://www.isleofmanfa.com/AboutUs/Contacts/Member+Clubs/|url-status=dead}}</ref> They were promoted to the top flight (then the First Division) in 1983\u201384 and stayed in the league just two years until the 1985\u201386 season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Isle of Man 1897/98 and 1970/71-1994/95|publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]]|date=29 May 2007|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesm/manx1898.html|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref> They were again promoted in the 1998\u201399 season,<ref>{{cite web|title=Isle of Man 1999/2000|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|date=9 May 2001|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesm/manx00.html|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref> but, as before, spent just two seasons in the top flight before finishing bottom in 2000\u201301, winning just two games all season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Isle of Man 2000/01|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|date=23 January 2003|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesm/manx01.html|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nUnion Mills currently compete in the [[Isle of Man Football League#Premier League|Premier League]]. They were promoted to the top flight in the [[Isle of Man League 2005-06|2005\u201306 season]] after winning Division Two. That same season they reached the Woods Cup Final where they lost to [[Colby F.C.|Colby]] 1\u20130 after extra time. They won the Paul Henry Gold Cup, beating [[Braddan F.C.|Braddan]] in the final 5\u20131.<ref name=rsssf06>{{cite web|title=Isle of Man 2005/06|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|date=20 August 2006|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesm/manx06.html|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref> In the [[Isle of Man League 2007\u201308|2007\u201308 season]] the club finished fifth in the Premier League<ref>{{cite web|title=Isle of Man 2007/08|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|date=22 August 2008|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesm/manx08.html|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe club has a Reserve team who compete in the [[Isle of Man Football Combination]]. They also have a youth system.\n\nOn 10 November 2007 former [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]] football [[Robbie Earle]] visited Union Mills, where he helped coach the club's Under-9's team.<ref>{{cite news|title=Robbie Earle drops in on Union Mills junior training session|work=Isle of Man Today|date=10 November 2007|url=http://www.iomtoday.co.im/video/Robbie-Earle-drops-in-on.3465835.jp|accessdate=12 November 2007|archivedate=28 November 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071128063727/http://www.iomtoday.co.im/video/Robbie-Earle-drops-in-on.3465835.jp|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the 2007\u201308 season Union Mills hosted the annual [[Isle of Man Football Association]] Awards at the Garey Mooar clubhouse on 27 June 2008.<ref>{{cite news|last=Faragher|first=Rick|title=Bass lands Footballer of the Year award|work=Isle of Man Today|date=2 July 2008|url=http://www.iomtoday.co.im/sport/isle-of-man-sport/bass-lands-footballer-of-the-year-award-1-1774172|accessdate=3 September 2008|archivedate=13 February 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160213082609/http://www.iomtoday.co.im/sport/isle-of-man-sport/bass-lands-footballer-of-the-year-award-1-1774172|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2011\u201312 season, Mills had their most successful run in the club's history. They won the Treble by clinching the Division 2 title, Wood's Cup beating [[Douglas Royal FC|Royals]] 3\u20131, Paul Henry Cup beating [[Marown FC|Marown]] 5\u20131, and also reached the final of the FA Cup, for the first time in the club's history, where they finished as runners up to [[St Georges A.F.C.|Geordies]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Millers complete the treble|work=Isle of Man Today|year=2012|url=http://www.iomtoday.co.im/sport/football-news/millers-complete-the-treble-1-4595619|accessdate=19 June 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223131546/http://www.iomtoday.co.im/sport/football-news/millers-complete-the-treble-1-4595619|archivedate=23 February 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2012\u201313 season, Mills made history again by reaching the Hospital Cup final for the 1st time and ended up being runners up to St Georges. \nShortly after this Derek Cowley announced plans to leave the club after 18 successful years in charge, his assistant Darren Scarffe also left the club.\n\nOn 16 June 2013 it was announced that Chris Cain would take over as being the new Union Mills manager.\n\nIn July 2018 Steven Fox was announced as Union Mills Manager\n\n==Link up with Blackpool F.C.==\nIn 2008 the club linked up with [[England|English]] football club [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] as a partner club in ''the Seasiders'' Centre of Excellence which has seen Blackpool visit Union Mills and continue to work with the club, staff and players.<ref>{{cite web|title=Partner clubs \u2013 Union Mills FC|publisher=[[Blackpool F.C.]]|url=http://www.blackpoolfcyouth.co.uk/site/page.asp?26|accessdate=3 September 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080903080630/http://www.blackpoolfcyouth.co.uk/site/page.asp?26|archivedate=3 September 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> As part of the link up Blackpool signed two players from the Isle of Man who attend the Centre of Excellence in [[Blackpool]].\n\nIn November 2008 Blackpool staff visited Union Mills, to help train the club's coaches, and announced that they would soon be opening a Development Centre on the island.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Centre of Excellence|journal=Up the Pool|volume=2008\u201309 season|issue=Blackpool vs Ipswich Town|pages=74|publisher=[[Blackpool F.C.]]|location=[[Blackpool]]|date=8 November 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Facilities==\nGarey Mooar is situated in a countryside location about one mile from Braddan Bridge and Union Mills. It has a new purpose built [[wikt:clubhouse|clubhouse]] with bar and clubroom. The club also has a 250 pitch [[campsite]] at Garey Mooar with breakfast and other meals available at the clubhouse.<ref>{{cite web|title=Union Mills Football Club|publisher=[[Isle of Man Government]]|year=2008|url=http://gov.im/tourism/travel/accommodation/properties/CC70T00045.qry?letter=U|accessdate=3 September 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080309045244/http://www.gov.im/tourism/travel/accommodation/properties/CC70T00045.qry?letter=U|archivedate=9 March 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> The club originally played on playing fields alongside Noble's Hospital, Braddan. In 2001 the club agreed to move from there to allow the site to be developed by the [[Department of Health and Social Security (Isle of Man)|Department of Health and Social Security]] (DHSS) for staff accommodation. New playing fields at Ballaotes Road were completed in 2002. In September 2004, construction began on the new clubhouse.<ref>{{cite web|title=First sod of earth cut for new Union Mills Football Club Clubhouse|publisher=Isle of Man Government|date=17 September 2004|url=http://gov.im/lib/news/dhss/firstsodofearthc.xml|accessdate=3 September 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721145740/http://gov.im/lib/news/dhss/firstsodofearthc.xml|archivedate=21 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> which was built with help and funding from the Football Foundation, who in March 2004 gave the club \u00a3382,312 toward the construction of the clubhouse and to add full-sized and junior [[Association football pitch|pitches]] for the club. Vince Watkins, Chairman of Union Mills, said at the time, \"We are delighted to receive this funding as it provides a significant proportion of the money we need to carry out the plans that we have been making for some years now. The move to Ballaoates will be a major benefit to the Club, its members and the wider community.\"<ref>{{cite press release|title=Manx club score football funding goal|publisher=Football Foundation|date=8 March 2004|url=http://www.footballfoundation.org.uk/media-centre/press-releases/?EntryId15=4456|accessdate=3 September 2008|archivedate=5 October 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005012007/http://www.footballfoundation.org.uk/media-centre/press-releases/?EntryId15=4456|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n\n===League===\n*'''Division Two (2)'''\n**Champions [[2005\u201306 Isle of Man League|2005\u201306]],<ref name=\"rsssf06\"/> [[2011\u201312 Isle of Man League|2011\u201312]]\n*'''Combination Division Two (2)'''\n**Champions (2): 2009\u201310\n\n===Cup===\n*'''Isle of Man Hospital Cup'''\n**Runners-up 2012\u201313\n*'''Isle of Man FA Cup'''\n**Runners-up 2011\u201312\n*'''Paul Henry Gold Cup (3)'''\n**Winners [[2004\u201305 Isle of Man League|2004\u201305]],<ref name=rsssfcup>{{cite web|title=Isle of Man \u2013 List of Cup Winners|publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]]|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesm/manxcuphist.html|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref> [[2005\u201306 Isle of Man League|2005\u201306]]<ref name=rsssf06/> 2011\u201312\n*'''Woods Cup (4)'''\n**Winners 1989\u201390,<ref name=rsssfcup/> 2002\u201303, [[2005\u201306 Isle of Man League|2005\u201306]],<ref name=\"rsssf06\"/> [[2011\u201312 Isle of Man League|2011\u201312]]<ref name=rsssfcup/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090426034610/http://www.umfc.tv/cms/ Official website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081011112539/http://full-time.thefa.com/Index.do?division=9756332 Sure Mobile Premier League League table at the Isle of Man FA website]\n\n{{Isle of Man Football League}}\n\n{{Coord|54.17870|N|4.50909|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Football clubs in the Isle of Man]]\n[[Category:1920 establishments in the Isle of Man]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1920]]\n", "name_user": "92.39.193.219", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHistory:Amended)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Union_Mills_F.C."}
{"title_page": "Daring (schooner)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|19th c. New Zealand schooner}}\n\n'''''Daring''''' was a 17-metre (55'8\") [[schooner]], launched on 1 September 1863 in [[Mangawhai]], New Zealand. It was wrecked twice, once in 1864, and again in 1865. ''Daring'''s wreck was excavated in December 2018 after being exposed by shifting sands.\n[[File:Daring_Schooner_Sketch.jpg|thumb|Sketch of Daring Schooner, NZ]]\n\n== Construction ==\n''Daring'' was a two-masted [[schooner]], built as a [[Cargo ship|cargo vessel]] in Mangawhai ship yard, New Zealand. Its construction was [[kauri]] [[Carvel (boat building)|carvel]] plank, with Muntz metal (60% Copper, 40% Zinc) on the hull. The ship was built by a Scottish boat builder, Donald McInnes. ''Daring'' was built for John Matheson and John Rattray, of Onehunga. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.classicyachtcharitabletrust.org.nz/trust_boats.htm?boat_id=17|title=Classic Yacht Daring|website=www.classicyachtcharitabletrust.org.nz|access-date=2019-03-05}}</ref>\n\n== First wreck and repairs ==\nOn 1 June 1864, little over a year after launching, ''Daring'' stranded on the South side of the bar at the mouth of the [[Waikato River]]. The vessel was originally reported to be a total wreck, but was subsequently repaired and re-floated. <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=New Zealand Shipwrecks 1795\u20131960|last=Ingram and Wheatley|first=C.W.N. and P.O.|publisher=A.H. & A.W. Reed|year=1960|location=182 Wakefield Street, Wellington, New Zealand|pages=88\u201389}}</ref>\n\n== Second wreck and total loss ==\nOn 22 February 1865, ''Daring'' was sailing from [[Taranaki]] to the [[Manukau]] with a cargo of grass seed. A severe gale arose when the vessel was offshore of the Kaipara Heads<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/auckland/local-news/nor-west-news/104287301/centuryold-schooner-uncovered-by-shifting-sand-at-muriwai-beach|title=Century-old schooner uncovered by shifting sand at Muriwai beach|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref>. It was blown on to the Rangahia Beach, near the South Head of [[Kaipara Harbour]]. The crew's attempts to keep the schooner off the beach were unsuccessful. She was left on the beach above the tide line. The crew rolled and jacked the vessel to the half tide mark, hoping to re-float her with the next full tide. A heavy gale began blowing on the morning of 23 February 1865, just before the full tide, and a heavy swell set in from the West. ''Daring'' was eventually driven back to her original position lower down the beach, and became a total loss. The ship and cargo of grass seed were uninsured.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== Re-discovery and recovery ==\nOn 27 May 2017, the remains of the wreck were spotted by a local resident.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/auckland/local-news/nor-west-news/104287301/centuryold-schooner-uncovered-by-shifting-sand-at-muriwai-beach|title=Century-old schooner uncovered by shifting sand at Muriwai beach|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref> The wreck had been uncovered by shifting sands having been abandoned and buried after wrecking on the beach.  \n\nAfter obtaining council permission, ''Daring'' was recovered on 12 December 2018 by the Daring Rescue Team, with assistance from the Classic Yacht Charitable Trust. Items abandoned with the wreck were also uncovered, including coins and a boot. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/auckland/109347118/rare-fully-intact-153yearold-ship-wreck-reveals-treasures--including-an-old-boot|title=Rare, fully intact 153-year-old shipwreck reveals treasures \u2013 including an old boot|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref>\n\n''Daring'' was relocated to Hobsonville, pending plans for its preservation and display. As of January 2019, ''Daring'' is supported by a scaffolding frame and covered with shrink wrap while stabilisation work is undertaken. Volunteers wet the timbers daily to ensure the wood does not split.<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://givealittle.co.nz/cause/daring-rescue/updates |title='Daring' Rescue. Recovering NZ's oldest ship. \u2013 Updates \u2013 Givealittle| website=givealittle.co.nz |language=en|access-date=2019-01-09}}</ref>\n \n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:1863 ships]]\n[[Category:Shipwrecks of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1864]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1865]]\n[[Category:History of the Auckland Region]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|19th c. New Zealand schooner}}\n\n'''''Daring''''' was a 17-metre (55'8\") [[schooner]], launched on 1 September 1863 in [[Mangawhai]], New Zealand. It was wrecked twice, once in 1864, and again in 1865. ''Daring'''s wreck was excavated in December 2018 after being exposed by shifting sands.\n[[File:Daring_Schooner_Sketch.jpg|thumb|Sketch of Daring Schooner, NZ]]\n\n== Construction ==\n''Daring'' was a two-masted [[schooner]], built as a [[Cargo ship|cargo vessel]] in Mangawhai ship yard, New Zealand. Its construction was [[kauri]] [[Carvel (boat building)|carvel]] plank, with Muntz metal (60% Copper, 40% Zinc) on the hull. The ship was built by a Scottish boat builder, Donald McInnes. ''Daring'' was built for John Matheson and John Rattray, of Onehunga. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.classicyachtcharitabletrust.org.nz/trust_boats.htm?boat_id=17|title=Classic Yacht Daring|website=www.classicyachtcharitabletrust.org.nz|access-date=2019-03-05}}</ref>\n\n== First Wreck and Repairs ==\nOn 1 June 1864, little over a year after launching, ''Daring'' stranded on the South side of the bar at the mouth of the [[Waikato River]]. The vessel was originally reported to be a total wreck, but was subsequently repaired and re-floated. <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=New Zealand Shipwrecks 1795-1960|last=Ingram and Wheatley|first=C.W.N. and P.O.|publisher=A.H. & A.W. Reed|year=1960|location=182 Wakefield Street, Wellington, New Zealand|pages=88-89}}</ref>\n\n== Second Wreck and Total Loss ==\nOn 22 February 1865, ''Daring'' was sailing from [[Taranaki]] to the [[Manukau]] with a cargo of grass seed. A severe gale arose when the vessel was offshore of the Kaipara Heads<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/auckland/local-news/nor-west-news/104287301/centuryold-schooner-uncovered-by-shifting-sand-at-muriwai-beach|title=Century-old schooner uncovered by shifting sand at Muriwai beach|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref>. It was blown on to the Rangahia Beach, near the South Head of [[Kaipara Harbour]]. The crew's attempts to keep the schooner off the beach were unsuccessful. She was left on the beach above the tide line. The crew rolled and jacked the vessel to the half tide mark, hoping to re-float her with the next full tide. A heavy gale began blowing on the morning of 23 February 1865, just before the full tide, and a heavy swell set in from the West. ''Daring'' was eventually driven back to her original position lower down the beach, and became a total loss. The ship and cargo of grass seed were uninsured.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== Re-discovery and recovery ==\nOn 27 May 2017, the remains of the wreck were spotted by a local resident on May 27.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/auckland/local-news/nor-west-news/104287301/centuryold-schooner-uncovered-by-shifting-sand-at-muriwai-beach|title=Century-old schooner uncovered by shifting sand at Muriwai beach|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref> The wreck had been uncovered by shifting sands having been abandoned and buried after wrecking on the beach.  \n\nAfter obtaining Council permission, ''Daring'' was recovered on 12 December 2018 by the Daring Rescue Team, with assistance from the Classic Yacht Charitable Trust. Items abandoned with the wreck were also uncovered, including coins and a boot. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/auckland/109347118/rare-fully-intact-153yearold-ship-wreck-reveals-treasures--including-an-old-boot|title=Rare, fully intact 153-year-old shipwreck reveals treasures - including an old boot|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref>\n\n''Daring'' was relocated to Hobsonville, pending plans for its preservation and display. As of January 2019, ''Daring'' is supported by a scaffolding frame and covered with shrink wrap while stabilization work is undertaken. Volunteers wet the timbers daily to ensure the wood does not split.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://givealittle.co.nz/cause/daring-rescue/updates|title='Daring' Rescue. Recovering NZ's oldest ship. - Updates - Givealittle|website=givealittle.co.nz|language=en|access-date=2019-01-09}}</ref>\n \n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:1863 ships]]\n[[Category:Shipwrecks of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1864]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1865]]\n[[Category:History of the Auckland Region]]\n", "name_user": "Schwede66", "label": "safe", "comment": "Sentence case for headings, fixeddashesusing ascript, date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daring_(schooner)"}
{"title_page": "OSIRIS-REx", "text_new": "{{Short description|A sample-return mission by NASA from asteroid 101955 Bennu}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox spaceflight |auto=all\n| name                  = OSIRIS-REx\n| names_list            = Origins, Spectral Interpretation, Resource Identification, Security, Regolith Explorer\n| image                 = OSIRIS-REx spacecraft model.png\n| image_caption         = Artist's rendering of the ''OSIRIS-REx'' spacecraft\n| image_size            = 275px\n\n| mission_type          = Asteroid sample return <ref name=\"pressrelease\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nasa.gov/home/hqnews/2011/may/HQ_11-163_New_Frontier.html|title=NASA To Launch New Science Mission To Asteroid In 2016|publisher=NASA|first=Dwayne C.|last=Brown|date=25 May 2011|accessdate=18 September 2016}}</ref>\n| operator              = [[NASA]] / [[Lockheed Martin]]\n| COSPAR_ID             = 2016-055A\n| SATCAT                = 41757\n| website               = www.asteroidmission.org\n| mission_duration      = 7 years (planned)<br/>{{spaces|15}}{{small|505 days at asteroid}}<br/>Elapsed: {{time interval|8 September 2016 23:05|show=ymd|sep=,}}<br/>{{spaces|15}}{{small|{{time interval|3 December 2018|show=d}} at asteroid}}\n\n| manufacturer          = [[Lockheed Martin Space Systems|Lockheed Martin]]\n| launch_mass           = {{convert|4650|lb|kg|order=flip}} <ref name=\"press kit\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nasa.gov/sites/default/files/atoms/files/osiris-rex_press_kit.pdf|title=OSIRIS-REx: Asteroid Sample Return Mission|type=Press Kit|publisher=NASA|date=August 2016|accessdate=18 September 2016}}</ref>\n| dry_mass              = {{convert|1940|lb|kg|order=flip}} <ref name=\"press kit\"/>\n| dimensions            = {{convert|8|xx|8|xx|10.33|ft|m|order=flip}} <ref name=\"press kit\"/>\n| power                 = 1226 to 3000 W <ref name=\"press kit\"/>\n\n| launch_date           = {{start-date|8 September 2016, 23:05}} [[UTC]] <ref name=\"nasasf20160908\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2016/09/atlas-v-osiris-rexs-round-trip-asteroid-bennu/ |title=Atlas V begins OSIRIS-REx's round trip to the asteroid Bennu|work=NASA Spaceflight|first=William|last=Graham|date=8 September 2016|accessdate=18 September 2016}}</ref>\n| launch_rocket         = [[Atlas V]] 411, AV-067 <ref name=\"nasasf20160908\"/>\n| launch_site           = [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station|Cape Canaveral]], [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station Space Launch Complex 41|SLC-41]]\n| launch_contractor     = [[United Launch Alliance]]\n\n| disposal_type         = <!--deorbited, decommissioned, placed in a graveyard orbit, etc-->\n| landing_date          = Planned: {{end-date|24 September 2023, 15:00}} UTC <ref name=\"astronow20160909\">{{cite news|url=https://astronomynow.com/2016/09/09/osiris-rex-probe-launched-to-asteroid-in-compelling-search-for-the-origins-of-life/|title=OSIRIS-REx probe launched to asteroid in compelling search for the origins of life|work=Astronomy Now|first=Justin|last=Ray|date=9 September 2016 |accessdate=18 September 2016}}</ref>\n| landing_site          = [[Utah Test and Training Range]] <ref name=\"astronow20160909\"/>\n\n|interplanetary         = \n {{Infobox spaceflight/IP\n  |type                 = flyby\n  |object               = [[Earth]]\n  |arrival_date         = 22 September 2017 <ref name=\"press kit\"/><ref name=\"earth flyby\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nasa.gov/feature/goddard/2017/osiris-rex-spacecraft-slingshots-past-earth |title=NASA'S OSIRIS-REx Spacecraft Slingshots Past Earth|publisher=[[NASA]]|date=2017-09-22|access-date=2018-04-26}}</ref>\n  |distance             = {{cvt|17237|km}} <ref name=\"earth flyby\"/>\n  | flyby               =\n  \n }}\n {{Infobox spaceflight/IP\n  |type                 = orbiter\n  |object               = [[101955 Bennu|Bennu]]\n  |arrival_date         = 31 December 2018 <ref name=orbit-insertion-31-Dec>{{cite web|url=https://www.asteroidmission.org/?latest-news=nasas-osiris-rex-spacecraft-arrives-asteroid-bennu|title=NASA'S OSIRIS-REx Spacecraft Arrives at Asteroid Bennu|publisher=NASA|date=3 December 2018|accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref><br/>(Rendezvous: 3 December 2018) \n  |departure_date       = 3 March 2021 (planned) <ref name=\"press kit\"/>\n  |sample_mass          = {{convert|60|g}} (planned) <ref name=\"astronow20160909\"/>\n }}\n\n| instruments_list = {{Infobox spaceflight/Instruments\n  | acronym1 = OCAMS  | name1 = OSIRIS-REx Camera Suite\n  | acronym2 = OLA    | name2 = OSIRIS-REx Laser Altimeter\n  | acronym3 = OTES   | name3 = OSIRIS-REx [[Thermal Emission Spectrometer]]\n  | acronym4 = OVIRS  | name4 = OSIRIS-REx Visible and Infrared Spectrometer\n  | acronym5 = REXIS  | name5 = Regolith X-ray Imaging Spectrometer\n  | acronym6 = TAGSAM | name6 = [[TAGSAM|Touch-And-Go Sample Acquisition Mechanism]]\n }}\n\n| programme         = '''[[New Frontiers program]]'''\n| previous_mission  = ''[[Juno (spacecraft)|Juno]]''\n| next_mission      = ''[[Dragonfly (spacecraft)|''Dragonfly'']]\n\n| insignia          = OSIRIS-REx mission logo (circa 2015).png\n| insignia_size     = 150x150px\n}}\n\nThe '''OSIRIS-REx''' ('''Origins, Spectral Interpretation, Resource Identification, Security, Regolith Explorer''') is a [[NASA]] asteroid study and [[sample-return mission]].<ref>\n* {{cite web|last1=Brown|first1=Dwayne|last2=Neal-Jones|first2=Nancy|title=RELEASE 15-056 - NASA's OSIRIS-REx Mission Passes Critical Milestone|url=http://www.nasa.gov/press/2015/march/nasa-s-osiris-rex-mission-passes-critical-milestone/|date=31 March 2015|work=[[NASA]]|accessdate=4 April 2015}}\n* {{cite news|last=Chang|first=Kenneth|title=NASA Aims at an Asteroid Holding Clues to the Solar System's Roots|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/06/science/nasa-osiris-rex-asteroid-bennu-sample.html |date=5 September 2016|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=6 September 2016}}\n* {{cite news|last=Corum|first=Jonathan|title=NASA Launches the Osiris-Rex Spacecraft to Asteroid Bennu|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2016/09/08/science/space/nasa-osiris-rex-launch.html|date=8 September 2016|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=9 September 2016}}\n* {{cite news|last=Chang|first=Kenneth|title=The Osiris-Rex Spacecraft Begins Chasing an Asteroid|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/09/science/nasa-launches-osiris-rex-spacecraft-to-retrieve-asteroid-pieces.html|date=8 September 2016|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=9 September 2016}}</ref> The mission's primary goal is to obtain a sample of at least {{convert|60|g}} from [[101955 Bennu]], a [[C-type asteroid|carbonaceous]] [[near-Earth object|near-Earth]] [[asteroid]], and return the sample to Earth for a detailed analysis. The material returned is expected to enable scientists to learn more about the [[formation and evolution of the Solar System]], its initial stages of planet formation, and the source of [[organic compound]]s that led to the [[Abiogenesis|formation of life]] on Earth.<ref name=selected>{{cite web|title=OSIRIS-REx Mission Selected for Concept Development|url=http://gsfctechnology.gsfc.nasa.gov/ORIRIS.htm|publisher=Goddard Space Flight Center|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120606151314/http://gsfctechnology.gsfc.nasa.gov/ORIRIS.htm|archivedate=6 June 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> If successful, OSIRIS-REx will be the first U.S. spacecraft to return samples from an asteroid. \n\nOSIRIS-REx was launched on 8 September 2016, flew past Earth on 22 September 2017, and reached the proximity of Bennu on 3 December 2018,<ref name=\"NYT-20181203\"/> where it began analyzing its surface for a target sample area over the next several months. On 12 December 2019, NASA announced the chosen landing spot, known as Nightingale.<ref name=\"site-selected\"/> It is expected to return with its sample to Earth on 24 September 2023.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ehpd.gsfc.nasa.gov/documents/552572main_OSIRIS_REx_Factsheet.pdf|title=OSIRIS-REx Factsheet|publisher=NASA/Explorers and Heliophysics Projects Division |date=August 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe cost of the mission is approximately {{US$|800 million}}<ref>{{cite news|title=NASA Aims to Grab Asteroid Dust in 2020|url=http://news.sciencemag.org/scienceinsider/2011/05/nasa-aims-to-grab-asteroid-dust.html|newspaper=Science Magazine|date=26 May 2011|access-date=26 May 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110529114319/http://news.sciencemag.org/scienceinsider/2011/05/nasa-aims-to-grab-asteroid-dust.html|archive-date=29 May 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> not including the [[Atlas V]] launch vehicle, which is about {{US$|183.5 million}}.<ref name=\"aug2013release\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nasa.gov/press/2013/august/nasa-selects-launch-services-contract-for-osiris-rex-mission/|title=NASA Selects Launch Services Contract for OSIRIS-REx Mission|last1=Buck|first1=Joshua |last2=Diller|first2=George|publisher=[[NASA]]|date=5 August 2013|accessdate=8 September 2013}}</ref> It is the third planetary science mission selected in the [[New Frontiers program]], after [[Juno (spacecraft)|''Juno'']] and ''[[New Horizons]]''. The [[principal investigator]] is [[Dante Lauretta]] from the [[University of Arizona]].\n\n==Mission==\n[[File:Asteroid-Bennu-OSIRIS-RExArrival-GifAnimation-20181203.gif|thumb|left|Asteroid Bennu, imaged by the OSIRIS-REx probe<br />(3 December 2018)]]\nOverall management, engineering and navigation for the mission is provided by [[NASA]]{{'s}} [[Goddard Space Flight Center]], while the [[University of Arizona]]{{'s}} [[Lunar and Planetary Laboratory]] provides principal science operations and [[Lockheed Martin Space Systems]] built the spacecraft and provides mission operations.<ref name=\"press kit\" /> The science team includes members from the United States, [[Canada]], [[France]], [[Germany]], [[United Kingdom]], and [[Italy]].<ref name=\"eoportal\">{{cite web |url=https://directory.eoportal.org/web/eoportal/satellite-missions/o/osiris-rex |title=OSIRIS-REx |work=Earth Observation Portal Directory |last=Kramer |first=Herbert J. |accessdate=20 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter traveling for approximately two years, the spacecraft [[Space rendezvous|rendezvoused]] with asteroid [[101955 Bennu]] in December 2018<ref name=nasa-20170109>{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/feature/goddard/2017/nasa-selects-participating-scientists-for-mission-to-asteroid-bennu|title=NASA Selects Participating Scientists for Mission to Asteroid Bennu|publisher=NASA |last=Hille|first=Karl|date=9 January 2018|accessdate=2 February 2018}}</ref> and began 505 days of surface mapping at a distance of approximately {{convert|5|km|mi}}.<ref name=\"pressrelease\"/> Results of that mapping will be used by the mission team to select the site from which to take a sample of the asteroid's surface.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.borntoengineer.com/nasa-successfully-launch-osiris-rex-asteroid-mission/|title=NASA Successfully Launch OSIRIS-REx Asteroid Mission|work=borntoengineer.com|date=9 September 2016|accessdate=9 September 2016}}</ref> Then a close approach (without landing) will be attempted to allow extension of a robotic arm to gather the sample.<ref>{{cite news|title=UA gets $1.2M to aid in asteroid mission|url=http://tucsoncitizen.com/morgue/2006/10/31/31046-ua-gets-1-2m-to-aid-in-asteroid-mission/|newspaper=Tucson Citizen|date=26 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nAn asteroid was chosen as the target of study because an asteroid is a \"[[time capsule]]\" from the birth of our [[Solar System]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.space.com/34007-nasa-launches-osiris-rex-asteroid-sampling-mission.html|title=Next Stop, Bennu! NASA Launches Bold Asteroid-Sampling Mission|work=Space.com|first=Mike|last=Wall|date=8 September 2016}}</ref> In particular, [[101955 Bennu]] was selected because of the availability of pristine [[carbonaceous]] material, a key element in [[Organic compound|organic molecules]] necessary for life as well as representative of matter from before the formation of Earth. Organic molecules, such as [[amino acid]]s, have previously been found in meteorite and comet samples, indicating that some ingredients necessary for life can be naturally synthesized in outer space.<ref name=pressrelease/>\n\n[[File:To Bennu and Back.webm|thumb|right|250px|OSIRIS-REx mission overview video]]\n\nFollowing a collection of material (60 grams), the sample will be returned to Earth in a {{convert|46|kg}} capsule similar to that which returned the samples of a comet [[81P/Wild]] on the [[Stardust (spacecraft)|Stardust spacecraft]]. The return trip to Earth will be shorter and the capsule will land with a parachute at the [[Utah Test and Training Range]] in September 2023 before being transported to the [[Johnson Space Center]] for processing in a dedicated research facility.<ref name=pressrelease/>\n\n===Launch===\n{{multiple image |align=right |direction=vertical |width=250\n |image1=Liftoff-of-OSIRIS-REx.ogg |caption1=OSIRIS-REx launch video\n |image2=Animation of OSIRIS-REx trajectory.gif |caption2=Animation of OSIRIS-REx{{'s}} trajectory from {{nowrap|9 September 2016}} to {{nowrap|3 December 2018}} <br /> {{legend2|magenta|OSIRIS-REx}}{{\u00b7}}{{legend2|lime|[[101955 Bennu]]}}{{\u00b7}}{{legend2|blue|Earth}}\n |image3=Animation of OSIRIS-Rex trajectory around 101955 Bennu.gif |caption3=Animation of OSIRIS-REx{{'s}} trajectory around [[101955 Bennu]] from {{nowrap|25 December 2018}}<br /> {{legend2|magenta|OSIRIS-REx}}{{\u00b7}}{{legend2|lime|101955 Bennu}}\n}}\n\nThe launch was on 8 September 2016 at 23:05 [[UTC]] on a [[United Launch Alliance]] [[Atlas V]] 411 from [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station|Cape Canaveral]], [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station Space Launch Complex 41|Space Launch Complex 41]].<ref name=\"nasasf20160908\"/> The 411 rocket configuration consists of a [[RD-180]] powered first stage with a single [[AJ-60A]] solid fuel booster, and a [[Centaur (rocket stage)|Centaur]] upper stage.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2016/09/atlas-v-osiris-rexs-round-trip-asteroid-bennu/|title=Atlas V begins OSIRIS-REx's round trip to the asteroid Bennu|work=[[NASASpaceFlight.com]]|first=William|last=Graham|date=8 September 2016}}</ref> OSIRIS-REx separated from the launch vehicle 55 minutes after ignition.<ref name=\"press kit\"/> The launch was declared \"exactly perfect\" by the mission's Principal Investigator, with no anomalies worked before or during launch.<ref name=\"exactlyperfect\">{{cite news|last1=Wall|first1=Mike|title='Exactly Perfect'! NASA Hails Asteroid Sample-Return Mission's Launch|url=http://www.space.com/34020-nasa-hails-osiris-rex-asteroid-mission-launch.html|work=Space.com|accessdate=10 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Cruise===\nOSIRIS-REx entered the cruise phase shortly after separation from the launch vehicle, following successful solar panel deployment, propulsion system initiation, and establishment of a communication link with Earth.<ref name=\"exactlyperfect\"/> Its hyperbolic escape speed from Earth was about {{convert|5.41|km/s|mi/s|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=OSIRIS-REx Mission & Trajectory Design|url=http://spaceflight101.com/osiris-rex/osiris-rex-mission-profile/|website=Spaceflight101.com|date=Sep 2016}}</ref> On 28 December 2016, the spacecraft successfully performed its first deep space maneuver to change its velocity by {{convert|431|m/s|km/h mph|abbr=on}} using {{convert|354|kg|lb|abbr=on}} of fuel.<ref name=\"nasa20170117\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/feature/goddard/2017/successful-deep-space-maneuver-for-nasa-s-osiris-rex-spacecraft |title=Successful Deep Space Maneuver for NASA's OSIRIS-REx Spacecraft |publisher=NASA |first=Nancy |last=Neal-Jones |date=17 January 2017 |accessdate=7 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"sfnow20170201\">{{cite news |url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2017/02/01/nasas-osiris-rex-probe-moonlights-as-asteroid-sleuth/ |title=NASA's OSIRIS-REx probe moonlights as asteroid sleuth |work=Spaceflight Now |first=Stephen |last=Clark |date=1 February 2017 |accessdate=9 March 2017}}</ref> An additional, smaller firing of its thrusters on 18 January further refined its course for an Earth [[gravity assist]] on 22 September 2017.<ref name=\"nasa20170117\" /> The cruise phase lasted until its encounter with Bennu in December 2018,<ref name=nasa-20170109 /> after which it entered its science and sample collection phase.<ref name=\"nasa20170117\" />\n\nDuring its cruise phase, OSIRIS-REx was used to search for a class of [[near-Earth object]]s known as [[Earth trojan|Earth-Trojan asteroids]] as it passed through Sun\u2013Earth {{L4}} Lagrange point. Between 9 and 20 February 2017, the OSIRIS-REx team used the spacecraft's MapCam camera to search for the objects, taking about 135 survey images each day for processing by scientists at the [[University of Arizona]]. The search was beneficial even though no new trojans were found,<ref name=\"trojanresults\">{{cite web|title=OSIRIS-REx Asteroid Search Tests Instruments|url=http://www.asteroidmission.org/?latest-news=osiris-rex-asteroid-search-tests-instruments-science-team|publisher=[[NASA]]|access-date=2018-12-20}}</ref> as it closely resembled the operation required as the spacecraft approached Bennu, searching for natural satellites and other potential hazards.<ref name=\"sfnow20170201\" /><ref name=\"nasa20170209\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/feature/goddard/2017/osiris-rex-begins-earth-trojan-asteroid-search |title=NASA's OSIRIS-REx Begins Earth-Trojan Asteroid Search |publisher=NASA |first1=Erin |last1=Morton |first2=Nancy |last2=Neal-Jones |date=9 February 2017 |accessdate=9 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 February 2017, while {{convert|673|e6km|e6mi|abbr=unit}} from [[Jupiter]], the PolyCam instrument aboard OSIRIS-REx successfully imaged the giant planet and three of its moons, [[Callisto (moon)|Callisto]], [[Io (moon)|Io]], and [[Ganymede (moon)|Ganymede]].<ref name=\"nasa20170215\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/image-feature/goddard/2017/osiris-rex-takes-closer-image-of-jupiter |title=NASA's OSIRIS-REx Takes Closer Image of Jupiter |publisher=NASA |date=15 February 2017 |accessdate=9 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nOSIRIS-REx flew by Earth on 22 September 2017.\n\n===Arrival and survey===\nOn 3 December 2018, NASA affirmed that OSIRIS-REx had matched the speed and orbit of Bennu at a distance of about {{convert|19|km|mi|sp=us}}, effectively reaching the asteroid. OSIRIS-REx performed closer passes of the Bennu surface, initially at about {{convert|6.5|km|mi|abbr=on}} through December to further refine the shape and orbit of Bennu. Preliminary spectroscopic surveys of the asteroid's surface by OSIRIS-REx spacecraft, detected the presence of [[Mineral hydration|hydrated minerals]] in the form of [[clay]]. While researchers suspect that Bennu was too small to host water, the hydroxyl groups may have come from water presence in its parent body before Bennu split off.<ref>{{cite web |title=NASA's Newly Arrived OSIRIS-REx Spacecraft Already Discovers Water on Asteroid |date=11 December 2018 |publisher=NASA |url=https://www.nasa.gov/press-release/nasa-s-newly-arrived-osiris-rex-spacecraft-already-discovers-water-on-asteroid}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2018/12/181210150554.htm  |title = Water found on asteroid, confirming Bennu as excellent mission target | date = 10 December 2018 | accessdate = 10 December 2018 | work = [[Science Daily]] }}</ref>\n\nOSIRIS-REx entered orbit around Bennu on 31 December 2018 at about {{convert|1.75|km|mi|abbr=on}} to start its extensive remote mapping and sensing campaign for the selection of a sample site. This is the closest distance that any spacecraft has orbited a celestial object, surpassing the [[Rosetta (spacecraft)|''Rosetta'']]{{'s}} orbit of comet [[67P/Churyumov\u2013Gerasimenko]] at {{convert|7|km|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"NYT-20181203\">{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/03/science/osiris-rex-bennu-asteroid-arrival.html | title= NASA's Osiris-Rex Arrives at Asteroid Bennu After a Two-Year Journey | first=  Kenneth | last = Chang | date = 3 December 2018 | accessdate = 3 December 2018 | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url = https://solarsystem.nasa.gov/news/805/nasas-osiris-rex-spacecraft-enters-close-orbit-around-bennu-breaking-record/ | title = NASA's OSIRIS-REx Spacecraft Enters Close Orbit Around Bennu, Breaking Record | first= Eric | last=  Morten | date = 31 December 2018 | accessdate = 1 January 2019 | publisher = [[NASA]] }}</ref> At this altitude, it takes the spacecraft 62 hours to orbit Bennu.<ref>[https://www.asteroidmission.org/?latest-news=nasas-osiris-rex-spacecraft-enters-close-orbit-around-bennu-breaking-record NASA's OSIRIS-REx Spacecraft Enters Close Orbit Around Bennu, Breaking Record]. Lonnie Shekhtman, OSIRIS-Rex Mission home page. 31 December 2018.</ref> At the end of this detailed survey, the spacecraft will enter a closer orbit with a radius of {{cvt|1|km|abbr=on}}.<ref>[https://www.asteroidmission.org/asteroid-operations/#detailedsurveybaseballdiamond Orbital B Phase. Osiris-Rex.] Accessed on 22 March 2018.</ref>\n\n===Sample acquisition===\n[[File:Artist's concept of OSIRIS-REx TAGSAM in operation.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Artist's concept of TAGSAM instrument in operation]]\nRehearsals will be performed before the sampling event, during which the solar arrays will be raised into a Y-shaped configuration to minimize the chance of dust accumulation during contact and provide more ground clearance in case the spacecraft tips over (up to 45\u00b0) during contact.<ref name=\"eoportal\"/> The descent will be very slow to minimize thruster firings prior to contact in order to reduce the likelihood of asteroid surface contamination by unreacted [[hydrazine]] propellant. Contact with the surface of Bennu will be detected using accelerometers, and the impact force will be dissipated by a spring in the TAGSAM arm.\n\nUpon surface contact by the TAGSAM instrument, a burst of [[nitrogen]] gas will be released, which will blow [[regolith]] particles smaller than {{convert|2|cm|in|1|abbr=on}} into the sampler head at the end of the robotic arm. A five-second timer will limit collection time to mitigate the chance of a collision. After the timer expires, the back-away maneuver will initiate a safe departure from the asteroid.<ref name=\"eoportal\"/>\n\nOSIRIS-REx will then halt the drift away from the asteroid in case it is necessary to return for another sampling attempt. The spacecraft will use images and spinning maneuvers to verify the sample has been acquired as well as determine its mass and verify it is in excess of the required {{convert|60|g|oz|1}}.<ref name=\"eoportal\"/> In the event of a failed sampling attempt, the spacecraft will return for another try. There is enough nitrogen gas for three attempts.<ref name=\"press kit\"/>\n\nIn addition to the bulk sampling mechanism, contact pads on the end of the sampling head will passively collect dust grains smaller than {{val|1|u=mm}}, upon contact with the asteroid. These pads are made from tiny loops of stainless steel.<ref name=\"DSLAURETTA\">{{cite web |url=https://dslauretta.com/2014/02/05/riding-the-vomit-comet/ |title=How Do We know When We Have Collected a Sample of Bennu? |website=Dslauretta.com |last=Lauretta |first=Dante |accessdate=23 August 2016|date=5 February 2014 }}</ref>\n\nAfter the sampling attempt, the Sample-Return Capsule (SRC) lid will be opened to allow the sampler head to be stowed. The arm will then be retracted into its launch configuration, and the SRC lid will be closed and latched preparing to return to [[Earth]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://spaceflight101.com/osiris-rex/osiris-rex-sample-return-capsule/ |title=Sample Return Capsule |work=Spaceflight101.com |accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:OSIRIS-REx candidate sample sites on Bennu.png|thumb|center|800px|The final four candidate sample sites]]\n\nNASA selected the final four candidate sample sites in August 2019, named Nightingale, Kingfisher, Osprey, and Sandpiper.<ref name=\"final four sample sites\">{{cite press release |title=NASA Mission Selects Final Four Site Candidates for Asteroid Sample Return |url=https://www.nasa.gov/press-release/nasa-mission-selects-final-four-site-candidates-for-asteroid-sample-return|agency= [[NASA]]|date= 2019-09-12|access-date=2019-12-28}}</ref> On December 12, 2019, they announced that Nightingale had been selected as the primary sample site and Osprey was selected as the backup site.<ref name=\"site-selected\">{{cite press release |title=X Marks the Spot: Sample Site Nightingale Targeted for Touchdown |url= https://www.asteroidmission.org/?latest-news=x-marks-the-spot-nasa-selects-site-for-asteroid-sample-collection |publisher=AsteroidMission.org |agency= [[NASA]]|date= 2019-12-12|access-date=2019-12-28}}</ref> Both located within craters, Nightingale is near Bennu's north pole while Osprey is near the equator. NASA plans to perform the actual sampling in late August, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.universetoday.com/145295/osiris-rex-did-its-closest-flyover-yet-just-250-meters-above-its-sample-site/|title=OSIRIS-REx did its Closest Flyover Yet, just 250 Meters Above its Sample Site|last=Gough|first=Evan|date=2020-03-09|website=Universe Today|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref>\n\n[[File:OSIRIS-REx Checkpoint Rehearsal.gif|thumb|The April 2020 sample collection rehearsal that brought OSIRIS-REx {{cvt|65|m}} from the surface. In this series of SamCam images the [[TAGSAM]] arm is fully extended and the Nightingale sample site comes into view at the top of the frame.]]\n\nOn April 15, 2020, a sample collection rehearsal was successfully coordinated over the Nightingale sample site. The exercise took OSIRIS-REx as close as {{convert|65|m}} from the surface before performing a back-away burn.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://phys.org/news/2020-04-closer-asteroid-bennu.html|title=One step closer to touching asteroid Bennu|last=Morton|first=Erin|date=April 16, 2020|website=Phys.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=OSIRIS-REx Buzzes Sample Site Nightingale|date=14 April 2020|url=https://www.asteroidmission.org/checkpoint-rehearsal-movie/|website=AsteroidMission.org|publisher=[[NASA]]|access-date= 16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Curation===\nOn 24 September 2023, the OSIRIS-REx return capsule will re-enter Earth's atmosphere and land under a parachute at the Air Force's [[Utah Test and Training Range]].<ref name=\"planetary20180705\">{{cite web |url=http://www.planetary.org/blogs/jason-davis/why-sample-return.html|title=What's the benefit of sample return?|publisher=The Planetary Society|first=Jason|last=Davis|date=5 July 2018|accessdate=2 September 2018}}</ref> The sample will be [[Extraterrestrial sample curation|curated]] at NASA's [[Astromaterials Research and Exploration Science Directorate]] (ARES) and at Japan's [[Extraterrestrial Sample Curation Center]].<ref name=\"planetary20180705\"/><ref name=\"jaxa-cur\">{{cite web|url=https://curation.isas.jaxa.jp/curation/osiris/index.html|title=OSIRIS-REx Project|publisher=JAXA/Astromaterial Science Research Group |accessdate=2 September 2018}}</ref> The sample material from the asteroid will be distributed to requesting organisations worldwide by ARES.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ares.jsc.nasa.gov/missions/osiris-rex/ |title=OSIRIS-REx|publisher=NASA/Astromaterials Research & Exploration Science Directorate|accessdate=2 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Name==\nOSIRIS-REx is an acronym, and each letter or combination of letters relates to part of the project:<ref name=\"asteroidmission.org\">[https://www.asteroidmission.org/objectives/osiris-rex-acronym/]</ref>\n\n*O \u2013 '''O'''rigins\n*SI \u2013 '''S'''pectral '''I'''nterpretation'''\n*RI \u2013 '''R'''esource '''I'''dentification\n*S \u2013 '''S'''ecurity\n*REx \u2013 '''R'''egolith '''Ex'''plorer\n\nEach of these words was chosen to represent an aspect of this mission.<ref name=\"asteroidmission.org\"/> For example, the S, for security means the security of Earth from hazardous NEO.<ref name=\"asteroidmission.org\"/> Specifically it refers to better understanding the [[Yarkovsky Effect]], that changes the trajectory of the asteroid.<ref name=\"asteroidmission.org\"/> Regolith Explorer means that the mission will study the texture, morphology, geochemistry, and spectral properties of the regolith of asteroid Bennu.<ref name=\"asteroidmission.org\"/>\n\nWhen its heritage concept was proposed in the Discovery program in 2004, it was called OSIRIS without the additional REx.<ref name=\"sci.esa.int\">[http://sci.esa.int/Conferences/MarcoPolo-ws08/The_OSIRIS_mission_-_Dante_Lauretta.pdf]</ref> This mission is also sometimes called New Frontiers 3, for it being the third of the New Frontiers program missions.<ref name=\"sci.esa.int\"/><ref>[https://supplychain.gsfc.nasa.gov/sites/supplychain/files/docs/2016/R.%20Perison%20-%20J.%20Dworkin%20-%20SC%202016.pdf]</ref>\n\nThe acronym OSIRIS was chosen in reference to the ancient mythological Egyptian god [[Osiris]], the underworld lord of the dead. He was classically depicted as a green-skinned man with a pharaoh's beard, partially mummy-wrapped at the legs and wearing a distinctive crown with two large ostrich feathers at either side.<ref name='NASAcronyms'>{{cite news|url=http://www.livescience.com/33309-nasa-acronyms-osiris-rex-asteroid-spacecraft-mission.html|title=NASAcronyms: How OSIRIS-REx Got Its Name|last=Wolchover|first=Natalie|work=LiveScience|date=27 May 2011|accessdate=12 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.space.com/11802-nasa-asteroid-mission-dangerous-1999-rq36.html|title=Why NASA Chose Potentially Threatening Asteroid for New Mission|last=Moskowitz|first=Clara|work=Space.com|date=27 May 2011 |accessdate=14 May 2017}}</ref> Rex means \"king\" in Latin. His name was chosen for this mission as [[101955 Bennu|asteroid Bennu]] is a threatening [[Impact event|Earth impactor]], with an estimated 1-in-1800 chance of hitting Earth in the year 2170.<ref name='NASAcronyms'/>\n\n==Science objectives==\n[[File:OSIRIS-REx StowCam first light.jpeg|thumb|Sample-return capsule as seen by StowCam]]\nThe science objectives of the mission are:<ref>[http://osiris-rex.lpl.arizona.edu/downloads/OSIRIS_REx_infosheet.pdf OSIRIS-Rex Infosheet] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120417120453/http://osiris-rex.lpl.arizona.edu/downloads/OSIRIS_REx_infosheet.pdf |date=17 April 2012 }} (PDF)</ref>\n#Return and analyze a sample of pristine [[C-type asteroid|carbonaceous asteroid]] regolith in an amount sufficient to study the nature, history, and distribution of its constituent minerals and [[organic compound]]s.\n#Map the global properties, chemistry, and mineralogy of a primitive carbonaceous asteroid to characterize its geologic and dynamic history and provide context for the returned samples.\n#Document the texture, morphology, geochemistry, and [[Spectroscopy|spectral properties]] of the regolith at the sampling site ''in situ'' at scales down to millimeters.\n#Measure the [[Yarkovsky effect]] (a thermal force on the object) on a potentially hazardous asteroid and constrain the asteroid properties that contribute to this effect.\n#Characterize the integrated global properties of a primitive carbonaceous asteroid to allow for direct comparison with ground-based telescopic data of the entire asteroid population.\n\n<!--I see no use for an old model of it shape when we have real images now. [[File:Bennu shape model.gif|thumb|right|Shape model of the mission's destination, asteroid Bennu]]-->\nTelescopic observations have helped define the orbit of [[101955 Bennu]], a [[near-Earth object]] with a mean diameter in the range of {{convert|480|to|511|m|ft|sp=us}}.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Physical properties of OSIRIS-REx target asteroid {{mp|101955|1999 RQ|36}}. Derived from Herschel, VLT/ VISIR, and Spitzer observations |journal=Astronomy & Astrophysics |first1=T. G. |last1=M\u00fcller |first2=L. |last2=O'Rourke |first3=A. M. |last3=Barucci |first4=A. |last4=P\u00e1l |first5=C. |last5=Kiss |first6=P. |last6=Zeidler |first7=B. |last7=Altieri |first8=B. M. |last8=Gonz\u00e1lez-Garc\u00eda |first9=M. |last9=K\u00fcppers |volume=548 |at=A36 |date=December 2012 |doi=10.1051/0004-6361/201220066 |bibcode=2012A&A...548A..36M |arxiv=1210.5370}}</ref> It completes an orbit of the [[Sun]] every 436.604 days (1.2 years). This orbit takes it close to the Earth every six years. Although the orbit is reasonably well known, scientists continue to refine it. It is critical to know the orbit of Bennu because recent calculations produced a cumulative probability of 1 in 1410 (or 0.071%) of impact with Earth in the period 2169 to 2199.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://neo.jpl.nasa.gov/risk/a101955.html |title=Earth Impact Risk Summary for 101955 Bennu |accessdate=29 April 2013 |date=5 August 2010 |work=Near Earth Object Program |publisher=NASA's JPL}}</ref> One of the mission objectives is to refine understanding of non-gravitational effects (such as the [[Yarkovsky effect]]) on this orbit, and the implications of those effects for Bennu's collision probability. Knowing Bennu's physical properties will be critical for future scientists to understand when developing an [[asteroid impact avoidance]] mission.<ref name=\"asteroidmission\">{{cite web |url=http://www.asteroidmission.org/mission/ |title=OSIRIS-REx - The Mission |work=Asteroidmission.org}}</ref>\n\nTelescopic observations have revealed some basic properties of Bennu. They indicate that it is very dark and is classified as a [[B-type asteroid]], a sub-type of the carbonaceous [[C-type asteroid]]s. Such asteroids are considered \"primitive\", having undergone little geological change from their time of formation.\n{{clear}}\n\n==Specifications==\n{{multiple image |direction=vertical |align=right |total_width=200\n |image1=OSIRIS-REx.stl |caption1=3D model of OSIRIS-REx\n |image2=OSIRIS-REx instrument deck.png |caption2=OSIRIS-REx instrument deck\n}}\n* Dimensions: Length {{convert|8|ft|m|1|order=flip|abbr=on}}, width {{convert|8|ft|m|1|order=flip|abbr=on}}, height {{convert|10.33|ft|m|1|order=flip|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"press kit\" />\n* Width with [[Solar panels on spacecraft|solar arrays]] deployed: {{convert|20.25|ft|m|1|order=flip|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"press kit\" />\n* Power: Two solar arrays generate {{val|1226|-|3000|u=watts}}, depending on the spacecraft's distance from the Sun. Energy is stored in [[Li-ion]] batteries.<ref name=\"press kit\" />\n* Propulsion system: Based on a [[hydrazine]] monopropellant system developed for the ''[[Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter]]'', carrying {{convert|2710|lb|kg|order=flip|abbr=on}} of propellant and helium.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dslauretta.com/2014/12/16/integration-of-the-osiris-rex-main-propellant-tank/ |title=Integration of the OSIRIS-REx Main Propellant Tank |website=Dslauretta.com |first=Dante |last=Lauretta |date=16 December 2014 |accessdate=20 April 2015}}</ref>\n* The Sample-Return Capsule (SRC) will re-enter the Earth's atmosphere for a parachute assisted landing. The capsule with encased samples will be retrieved from Earth's surface and studied, as was done with the ''[[Stardust (spacecraft)|Stardust]]'' mission.\n\n==Payload==\nIn addition to its telecommunication equipment, the spacecraft will carry a suite of instruments that will study the asteroid in many wavelengths,<ref name=\"instruments\" /> as well as image the asteroid, and retrieve a physical sample to return to Earth. [[The Planetary Society]] coordinated a campaign to invite interested persons to have their names or artwork on the mission's spirit of exploration saved on a microchip now carried in the spacecraft.<ref>\n*{{cite news |url=http://www.asteroidmission.org/?latest-news=nasa-invites-public-send-artwork-asteroid |title=NASA Invites Public to Send Artwork to an Asteroid |publisher=University of Arizona |date=19 February 2016 |accessdate=1 April 2016}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.planetary.org/get-involved/messages/bennu/ |title=OSIRIS-REx: Messages to Bennu! |publisher=The Planetary Society |accessdate=10 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n===OCAMS===\n[[File:Osiris-Rex Ocams 007.jpg|thumb|Imaging camera suite]]\nThe OSIRIS-REx Camera Suite (OCAMS) consists of the PolyCam, the MapCam, and the SamCam.<ref name=\"instruments\">{{cite web |url=http://www.asteroidmission.org/objectives/instruments/ |title=Instruments: Science Payload |publisher=University of Arizona |accessdate=18 September 2016}}</ref> Together they acquire information on asteroid Bennu by providing global mapping, sample site reconnaissance and characterization, high-resolution imaging, and records of the sample acquisition.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://dslauretta.com/2014/01/11/ocams-the-eyes-of-osiris-rex/ |title=OCAMS \u2013 The Eyes of OSIRIS-REx |website=Dslauretta.com |first=Dante |last=Lauretta |date=11 January 2014 |accessdate=10 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n*PolyCam, an {{convert|8|in|cm|adj=on}} telescope, acquires images with increasingly higher resolution as the spacecraft approaches the asteroid.\n*MapCam searches for satellites and outgassing plumes. It maps the asteroid in 4 different colors, informs the model of Bennu's shape and provides high resolution imaging of the potential sample sites.\n*SamCam continuously documents the sample acquisitions.\n\n===OLA===\nThe OSIRIS-REx Laser Altimeter (OLA) is a scanning and [[LIDAR]] instrument that will provide high resolution topographical information throughout the mission.<ref name=\"instruments\" /> The information received by OLA creates global [[topographic]] maps of Bennu, local maps of candidate sample sites, ranging in support of other instruments, and support navigation and gravity analyses.\n\nOLA scans the surface of Bennu at specific intervals to rapidly map the entire surface of the asteroid to achieve its primary objective of producing local and global topographic maps. The data collected by OLA will also be used to develop a control network relative to the center of mass of the asteroid and to enhance and refine gravitational studies of Bennu.\n\nOLA has a single common receiver and two complementary transmitter assemblies that enhance the resolution of the information brought back. OLA's high-energy laser transmitter is used for ranging and mapping from {{convert|1|to|7.5|km|mi|1|abbr=on}}. The low-energy transmitter is used for ranging and imaging from {{convert|0.5|to|1|km|mi|1|abbr=on}}. The repetition rate of these transmitters sets the data acquisition rate of OLA. Laser pulses from both the low and high energy transmitters are directed onto a movable scanning mirror, which is co-aligned with the field of view of the receiver telescope limiting the effects of background solar radiation. Each pulse provides target range, azimuth, elevation, received intensity and a time-tag.\n\nOLA was funded by the [[Canadian Space Agency]] (CSA) and was built by [[MacDonald, Dettwiler and Associates]] at Brampton, Ontario, Canada.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.asc-csa.gc.ca/eng/satellites/osiris-rex/ola.asp |title=OLA, Canada's Contribution to OSIRIS-REx |work=Canadian Space Agency |date=4 March 2013 |accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref> OLA was delivered for integration with the spacecraft on 17 November 2015.<ref>\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/content/goddard/canada-contributes-to-nasa-s-osiris-rex-mission |title=Canada Contributes to NASA's OSIRIS-REx Mission |publisher=NASA |first=Nancy N. |last=Jones |date=17 July 2014}}\n*{{cite news |url=https://www.kelownanow.com/news/news/National_News/15/12/17/Canada_to_Invest_in_Space_Exploration_with_New_Laser/ |title=Canada to Invest in Space Exploration with New Laser |work=Kelowna Now |first=Cassandra |last=Jeffery |date=17 December 2015}}</ref> The lead instrument scientist of OLA is Michael Daly from [[York University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asc-csa.gc.ca/eng/satellites/osiris-rex/canadas-role.asp|title=Canada's role in OSIRIS-REx|date=4 March 2013|website=www.asc-csa.gc.ca|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\n===OVIRS===\n[[File:Osiris-Rex Ovirs gsfc 20150619 2015-12655 019-023.jpg|thumb|OVIRS]]\nThe OSIRIS-REx Visible and IR Spectrometer (OVIRS) is a [[spectrometer]], which measures light to provide mineral and organic spectral maps and local spectral information of candidate sample sites.<ref name=\"instruments\" /> It also provides full-disc asteroid spectral data, global spectral maps (20&nbsp;m resolution), and spectra of the sample site (blue to near-infrared, {{nowrap|400\u20134,300 nm}}, with a [[spectral resolution]] of {{nowrap|7.5\u201322 nm}}).<ref name=\"simonmiller2013\">{{cite conference |url=http://www.lpi.usra.edu/meetings/lpsc2013/pdf/1100.pdf |title=OSIRIS-REx OVIRS: A Scalable Visible to Near-IR Spectrometer for Planetary Study |conference=44th Lunar and Planetary Science Conference. 18\u201322 March 2013. The Woodlands, Texas. |first1=A. A. |last1=Simon-Miller |first2=D. C. |last2=Reuter |date=2013 |bibcode=2013LPI....44.1100S}}</ref> These data will be used in concert with OTES spectra to guide sample-site selection. These spectral ranges and resolving powers are sufficient to provide surface maps of mineralogical and molecular components including [[carbonate]]s, [[silicate]]s, [[sulfate]]s, [[oxide]]s, [[Adsorption#Adsorbed water|adsorbed water]] and a wide range of [[organic compound]]s. It provides at least two spectral samples per resolution [[Chemical element|element]] taking full advantage of the spectral resolution.{{Clarify|reason=What does this sentence mean?|date=January 2020}}\n\n===OTES===\n[[File:Osiris-Rex Otes-3.jpg|thumb|right|OTES]]\nThe OSIRIS-REx Thermal Emission Spectrometer (OTES) provides mineral and [[thermal infrared spectroscopy|thermal emission spectral]] maps and local spectral information of candidate sample sites by collecting [[Infrared spectroscopy|thermal infrared]] data from 4\u201350&nbsp;\u00b5m.<ref name=\"instruments\" />\n\nOTES provides full-disc Bennu spectral data, global spectral maps, and local sample site spectral information used to characterize the global, regional, and local mineralogic composition and thermal emission from the asteroid surface. The [[wavelength]] range, spectral resolution, and radiometric performance are sufficient to resolve and identify the key vibrational absorption features of silicate, carbonate, sulfate, phosphate, oxide, and hydroxide minerals. OTES is also used to measure the total thermal emission from Bennu in support of the requirement to measure emitted radiation globally. Based on the performance of [[Mini-TES]] in the dusty surface environment of Mars, OTES was designed to be resilient to extreme dust contamination on the optical elements.\n\n===REXIS===\nThe Regolith X-ray Imaging Spectrometer (REXIS) will provide an [[X-ray spectroscopy]] map of Bennu to constrain the element abundances. It complements core OSIRIS-REx mission science.<ref name=\"instruments\" /> REXIS is a collaborative development by four groups within [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (MIT) and [[Harvard University]], with the potential to involve more than 100 students throughout the process. REXIS is based on flight heritage hardware, thereby minimizing elements of technical risk, schedule risk, and cost risk.\n\nREXIS is a [[coded aperture]] soft X-ray (0.3\u20137.5&nbsp;keV) telescope that images X-ray fluorescence line emission produced by the interaction of solar [[X-rays]] and the [[solar wind]] with the regolith of Bennu. Images are formed with 21 [[Minute of arc|arcminute]] resolution (4.3&nbsp;m spatial resolution at a distance of 700&nbsp;m). Imaging is achieved by correlating the detected X-ray image with a 64 x 64 element random mask (1.536&nbsp;mm pixels). REXIS will store each X-ray event data in order to maximize the data storage usage and to minimize the risk. The [[pixel]]s will be addressed in 64 x 64 bins and the 0.3\u20137.5&nbsp;keV range will be covered by five broad bands and 11 narrow line bands. A 24&nbsp;s resolution time tag will be interleaved with the event data to account for Bennu rotation. Images will be reconstructed on the ground after downlink of the event list. Images are formed simultaneously in 16 energy bands centered on the dominant lines of abundant surface elements from O-K (0.5&nbsp;keV) to Fe-K\u00df (7&nbsp;keV) as well the representative continuum. During orbital phase 5B, a 21-day orbit 700&nbsp;m from the surface of Bennu, a total of at least 133 events/asteroid pixel/energy band are expected under 2&nbsp;keV; enough to obtain significant constraints on element abundances at scales larger than 10&nbsp;m.\n\nOn 11 November 2019, university students and researchers involved in the mission accidentally discovered X-ray burst from a [[black hole]] name MAXI J0637-430 locate 30,000 light-years away, during observing the asteroid with REXIS.<ref>{{cite web| title = OSIRIS-REx Observes a Black Hole\n | date = 3 March 2020| publisher = NASA Goddard | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Erry315AwmI | access-date = 5 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===TAGSAM===\n[[File:Osiris-Rex Sample-return-arm-test-167.jpg|thumb|TAGSAM arm test before launch]]\n{{main|TAGSAM}}\nThe sample-return system, called Touch-And-Go Sample Acquisition Mechanism (TAGSAM), consists of a sampler head with an articulated {{convert|3.35|m|ft|0|adj=on|sp=us}} arm.<ref name=\"press kit\" /><ref name=\"instruments\" /> An on-board nitrogen source will support up to three separate sampling attempts for a minimum total amount of {{convert|60|g}} of sample. The surface contact pads will also collect fine-grained material.\n\nHighlights of the TAGSAM instrument and technique include:\n* Slowly approach surface at {{convert|0.2|m/s|sp=us}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://dslauretta.com/2013/11/27/how-to-get-to-bennu-and-back/ |title=How To Get To Bennu and Back |website=Dslauretta.com |first=Dante |last=Lauretta |date=27 November 2013 |accessdate=10 September 2016}}</ref>\n* Contact within {{convert|25|m|sp=us}} of selected location\n* OCAMS documents sampling at 1&nbsp;Hz\n* Collect samples in less than five seconds, direct nitrogen (N<sub>2</sub>) annular jet fluidizes regolith, surface-contact pad captures surface sample\n* Verify bulk sample collection via spacecraft inertia change; surface sample by imaging sampler head\n* Sampler head stored in Sample-Return Capsule (SRC) and returned to Earth\n{{clear}}\n\n== Cooperation with JAXA ==\n[[Hayabusa2]] is a similar mission from [[JAXA]] to collect a sample from near-Earth asteroid [[162173 Ryugu]]. It arrived at the asteroid in June 2018 and left in November 2019 after two successful sample collections. Due to the similarity and overlapping timelines of the two missions, NASA and JAXA signed an agreement to collaborate on sample exchange and research.<ref>{{cite web |title= NASA, JAXA reach asteroid sample-sharing agreement | first1 = Stephen | last1 = Clark | publisher = Spaceflight Now| date= 15 December 2014|url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2014/12/15/nasa-jaxa-reach-asteroid-sample-sharing-agreement/|access-date = 12 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title = NASA, Curation Preparation for Ryugu Sample Returned by JAXA's Hayabusa2 Mission|publisher = [[NASA]] |first1=Keiko |last1=Nakamura-Messenger |first2 = Kevin |last2 = Righter | first3  = Christopher | last3 = Snead | first4 = Francis | last4 = McCubbin | first5 = Lisa | last5 =  Pace | first6 = Ryan | last6 = Zeigler | first7 = Cindy | last7 = Evans| year = 2017| url = https://ntrs.nasa.gov/archive/nasa/casi.ntrs.nasa.gov/20170008918.pdf|access-date = 12 February 2020}}</ref> The two teams visited each other, with representatives from JAXA visiting the OSIRIS-REx Science Operations Center at the University of Arizona, and members of the OSIRIS-REx team traveling to Japan to meet with the Hayabusa2 team.<ref>{{cite web|title = Mission Update Apr. 22, 2019|date = 22 April 2019| url = https://www.asteroidmission.org/?mission_update=apr-22-2019| website = AsteroidMission.org| publisher = [[NASA]] | access-date = 12 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title =This week we're hosting Science Team Meeting 12 at @uarizona. More than 100 members of @nasa's OSIRIS-REx team and @jaxajp's Hayabusa2 team are gathered in Tucson to exchange information, share ideas and plan ways the two #asteroid-bound missions can collaborate. #science|website=Instagram|publisher = OSIRIS-REx |date = 29 March 2017|url = https://www.instagram.com/p/BSO5YjKBLwf/|access-date = 12 February 2020}}</ref> The teams are sharing software, data, and techniques for analysis, and will eventually exchange portions of the samples that are returned to Earth.<ref>{{cite web|title =Two Pieces of a Cosmic Puzzle: Hayabusa2 and OSIRIS-REx| first1= Christine |last1 = Hoekenga| date= 22 June 2018|website= AsteroidMission.org| publisher = [[NASA]]| url = https://www.asteroidmission.org/?latest-news=two-pieces-cosmic-puzzle-hayabusa2-osiris-rex | access-date = 12 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title = Collaboration Between OSIRIS-REx and Hayabusa2 | first1 = Dante | last1 = Lauretta| date = 20 October 2014| publisher = [[The Planetary Society]] | url = https://www.planetary.org/blogs/guest-blogs/dante-lauretta/20141020-collaboration-between.html | access-date = 12 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==OSIRIS-REx II==\nOSIRIS-REx II was a 2012 mission concept to replicate the original spacecraft for a double mission, with the second vehicle collecting samples from the two moons of Mars, [[Phobos (moon)|Phobos]] and [[Deimos (moon)|Deimos]]. It was stated that this mission would be both the quickest and least expensive way to get samples from the moons.<ref>{{cite conference |url=http://www.lpi.usra.edu/meetings/marsconcepts2012/pdf/4017.pdf |title=OSIRIS-REx II to Mars - Mars Sample Return from Phobos and Deimos |conference=Concepts and Approaches for Mars Exploration. 12\u201314 June 2012. Houston, Texas. |first=T. L. |last=Elifritz |date=2012 |bibcode=2012LPICo1679.4017E}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.extremetech.com/extreme/229171-osiris-rex-is-about-to-go-collect-and-return-samples-from-an-asteroid |title=OSIRIS-REx is about to go collect (and return) samples from an asteroid |work=ExtremeTech |first=Graham |last=Templeton |date=31 May 2016 |accessdate=24 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n{{multiple images |align=center |direction=horizontal |header=Views from OSIRIS REx |total_width = 1200\n|image1=NASA\u2019s_OSIRIS-REx_Captures_New_Earth-Moon_Image_(cropped).png |caption1=Earth-Moon system during an engineering test (January 2018).\n|image2=OSIRIS-REx_First_Image_of_Asteroid_Bennu.gif |caption2=First images of asteroid Bennu (August 2018).\n|image3=NASA-EarthMoonLowerLeft-BennuAsteroidUpperRight-20190108.jpg |caption3=Earth-Moon (lower left) and asteroid Bennu (upper right) (December 2018).<ref name=\"AP-20190108\">{{cite news |last=Dunn |first=Marcia |title=Asteroid-circling spacecraft grabs cool snapshot of home width2=200|url=https://apnews.com/de76da4abcc04c288109201c33e22a2c |date=8 January 2019 |work=[[AP News]] |accessdate=8 January 2019 }}</ref>\n|image4=OSIRIX-REx views Asteroid Bennu.jpg |caption4=Asteroid Bennu from {{convert|330|km|mi|abbr=on}} away (29 October 2018).\n|image5=OSIRIS-REx SRC and Bennu.png|caption5 = The Sample Return Capsule (SRC) with asteroid Bennu in the background (December 2019).\n|footer=\n}}\n\n==See also==\n\n* {{annotated link|Asteroidal water}}\n* {{annotated link|Hayabusa}}\n* {{annotated link|Hayabusa2}}\n* {{annotated link|List of asteroids visited by spacecraft}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|OSIRIS-REx}}\n* [http://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/osiris-rex/ OSIRIS-REx website] at NASA\n* [http://www.asteroidmission.org OSIRIS-REx website] at the University of Arizona\n* [https://pdssbn.astro.umd.edu/data_sb/missions/orex/index.shtml ''OSIRIS-REx'' Mission Archive] at the NASA Planetary Data System, Small Bodies Node\n\n{{Asteroid spacecraft}}\n{{Planetary Missions Program Office|New Frontiers=y}}\n{{Planetary defense}}\n{{Astrobiology}}\n{{Solar System probes}}\n{{Orbital launches in 2016}}\n{{2016 in space}}\n{{2018 in space}}\n{{2020 in space}}\n{{Portal bar|Astronomy|Space|Spaceflight}}\n\n[[Category:OSIRIS-REx| ]]\n[[Category:NASA space probes]]\n[[Category:Space probes launched in 2016]]\n[[Category:Missions to near-Earth asteroids]]\n[[Category:New Frontiers program]]\n[[Category:Astrobiology space missions]]\n[[Category:Planetary defense]]\n[[Category:Sample return missions]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched by Atlas rockets]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|A sample-return mission by NASA from asteroid 101955 Bennu}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox spaceflight |auto=all\n| name                  = OSIRIS-REx\n| names_list            = Origins, Spectral Interpretation, Resource Identification, Security, Regolith Explorer\n| image                 = OSIRIS-REx spacecraft model.png\n| image_caption         = Artist's rendering of the ''OSIRIS-REx'' spacecraft\n| image_size            = 275px\n\n| mission_type          = Asteroid sample return <ref name=\"pressrelease\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nasa.gov/home/hqnews/2011/may/HQ_11-163_New_Frontier.html|title=NASA To Launch New Science Mission To Asteroid In 2016|publisher=NASA|first=Dwayne C.|last=Brown|date=25 May 2011|accessdate=18 September 2016}}</ref>\n| operator              = [[NASA]] / [[Lockheed Martin]]\n| COSPAR_ID             = 2016-055A\n| SATCAT                = 41757\n| website               = www.asteroidmission.org\n| mission_duration      = 7 years (planned)<br/>{{spaces|15}}{{small|505 days at asteroid}}<br/>Elapsed: {{time interval|8 September 2016 23:05|show=ymd|sep=,}}<br/>{{spaces|15}}{{small|{{time interval|3 December 2018|show=d}} at asteroid}}\n\n| manufacturer          = [[Lockheed Martin Space Systems|Lockheed Martin]]\n| launch_mass           = {{convert|4650|lb|kg|order=flip}} <ref name=\"press kit\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nasa.gov/sites/default/files/atoms/files/osiris-rex_press_kit.pdf|title=OSIRIS-REx: Asteroid Sample Return Mission|type=Press Kit|publisher=NASA|date=August 2016|accessdate=18 September 2016}}</ref>\n| dry_mass              = {{convert|1940|lb|kg|order=flip}} <ref name=\"press kit\"/>\n| dimensions            = {{convert|8|xx|8|xx|10.33|ft|m|order=flip}} <ref name=\"press kit\"/>\n| power                 = 1226 to 3000 W <ref name=\"press kit\"/>\n\n| launch_date           = {{start-date|8 September 2016, 23:05}} [[UTC]] <ref name=\"nasasf20160908\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2016/09/atlas-v-osiris-rexs-round-trip-asteroid-bennu/ |title=Atlas V begins OSIRIS-REx's round trip to the asteroid Bennu|work=NASA Spaceflight|first=William|last=Graham|date=8 September 2016|accessdate=18 September 2016}}</ref>\n| launch_rocket         = [[Atlas V]] 411, AV-067 <ref name=\"nasasf20160908\"/>\n| launch_site           = [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station|Cape Canaveral]], [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station Space Launch Complex 41|SLC-41]]\n| launch_contractor     = [[United Launch Alliance]]\n\n| disposal_type         = <!--deorbited, decommissioned, placed in a graveyard orbit, etc-->\n| landing_date          = Planned: {{end-date|24 September 2023, 15:00}} UTC <ref name=\"astronow20160909\">{{cite news|url=https://astronomynow.com/2016/09/09/osiris-rex-probe-launched-to-asteroid-in-compelling-search-for-the-origins-of-life/|title=OSIRIS-REx probe launched to asteroid in compelling search for the origins of life|work=Astronomy Now|first=Justin|last=Ray|date=9 September 2016 |accessdate=18 September 2016}}</ref>\n| landing_site          = [[Utah Test and Training Range]] <ref name=\"astronow20160909\"/>\n\n|interplanetary         = \n {{Infobox spaceflight/IP\n  |type                 = flyby\n  |object               = [[Earth]]\n  |arrival_date         = 22 September 2017 <ref name=\"press kit\"/><ref name=\"earth flyby\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nasa.gov/feature/goddard/2017/osiris-rex-spacecraft-slingshots-past-earth |title=NASA'S OSIRIS-REx Spacecraft Slingshots Past Earth|publisher=[[NASA]]|date=2017-09-22|access-date=2018-04-26}}</ref>\n  |distance             = {{cvt|17237|km}} <ref name=\"earth flyby\"/>\n  | flyby               =\n  \n }}\n {{Infobox spaceflight/IP\n  |type                 = orbiter\n  |object               = [[101955 Bennu|Bennu]]\n  |arrival_date         = 31 December 2018 <ref name=orbit-insertion-31-Dec>{{cite web|url=https://www.asteroidmission.org/?latest-news=nasas-osiris-rex-spacecraft-arrives-asteroid-bennu|title=NASA'S OSIRIS-REx Spacecraft Arrives at Asteroid Bennu|publisher=NASA|date=3 December 2018|accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref><br/>(Rendezvous: 3 December 2018) \n  |departure_date       = 3 March 2021 (planned) <ref name=\"press kit\"/>\n  |sample_mass          = {{convert|60|g}} (planned) <ref name=\"astronow20160909\"/>\n }}\n\n| instruments_list = {{Infobox spaceflight/Instruments\n  | acronym1 = OCAMS  | name1 = OSIRIS-REx Camera Suite\n  | acronym2 = OLA    | name2 = OSIRIS-REx Laser Altimeter\n  | acronym3 = OTES   | name3 = OSIRIS-REx [[Thermal Emission Spectrometer]]\n  | acronym4 = OVIRS  | name4 = OSIRIS-REx Visible and Infrared Spectrometer\n  | acronym5 = REXIS  | name5 = Regolith X-ray Imaging Spectrometer\n  | acronym6 = TAGSAM | name6 = [[TAGSAM|Touch-And-Go Sample Acquisition Mechanism]]\n }}\n\n| programme         = '''[[New Frontiers program]]'''\n| previous_mission  = ''[[Juno (spacecraft)|Juno]]''\n| next_mission      = ''[[Dragonfly (spacecraft)|''Dragonfly'']]\n\n| insignia          = OSIRIS-REx mission logo (circa 2015).png\n| insignia_size     = 150x150px\n}}\n\nThe '''OSIRIS-REx''' ('''Origins, Spectral Interpretation, Resource Identification, Security, Regolith Explorer''') is a [[NASA]] asteroid study and [[sample-return mission]].<ref>\n* {{cite web|last1=Brown|first1=Dwayne|last2=Neal-Jones|first2=Nancy|title=RELEASE 15-056 - NASA's OSIRIS-REx Mission Passes Critical Milestone|url=http://www.nasa.gov/press/2015/march/nasa-s-osiris-rex-mission-passes-critical-milestone/|date=31 March 2015|work=[[NASA]]|accessdate=4 April 2015}}\n* {{cite news|last=Chang|first=Kenneth|title=NASA Aims at an Asteroid Holding Clues to the Solar System's Roots|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/06/science/nasa-osiris-rex-asteroid-bennu-sample.html |date=5 September 2016|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=6 September 2016}}\n* {{cite news|last=Corum|first=Jonathan|title=NASA Launches the Osiris-Rex Spacecraft to Asteroid Bennu|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2016/09/08/science/space/nasa-osiris-rex-launch.html|date=8 September 2016|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=9 September 2016}}\n* {{cite news|last=Chang|first=Kenneth|title=The Osiris-Rex Spacecraft Begins Chasing an Asteroid|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/09/science/nasa-launches-osiris-rex-spacecraft-to-retrieve-asteroid-pieces.html|date=8 September 2016|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=9 September 2016}}</ref> The mission's primary goal is to obtain a sample of at least {{convert|60|g}} from [[101955 Bennu]], a [[C-type asteroid|carbonaceous]] [[near-Earth object|near-Earth]] [[asteroid]], and return the sample to Earth for a detailed analysis. The material returned is expected to enable scientists to learn more about the [[formation and evolution of the Solar System]], its initial stages of planet formation, and the source of [[organic compound]]s that led to the [[Abiogenesis|formation of life]] on Earth.<ref name=selected>{{cite web|title=OSIRIS-REx Mission Selected for Concept Development|url=http://gsfctechnology.gsfc.nasa.gov/ORIRIS.htm|publisher=Goddard Space Flight Center|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120606151314/http://gsfctechnology.gsfc.nasa.gov/ORIRIS.htm|archivedate=6 June 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> If successful, OSIRIS-REx will be the first U.S. spacecraft to return samples from an asteroid. \n\nOSIRIS-REx was launched on 8 September 2016, flew past Earth on 22 September 2017, and reached the proximity of Bennu on 3 December 2018,<ref name=\"NYT-20181203\"/> where it began analyzing its surface for a target sample area over the next several months. On 12 December 2019, NASA announced the chosen landing spot, known as Nightingale.<ref name=\"site-selected\"/> It is expected to return with its sample to Earth on 24 September 2023.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ehpd.gsfc.nasa.gov/documents/552572main_OSIRIS_REx_Factsheet.pdf|title=OSIRIS-REx Factsheet|publisher=NASA/Explorers and Heliophysics Projects Division |date=August 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe cost of the mission is approximately {{US$|800 million}}<ref>{{cite news|title=NASA Aims to Grab Asteroid Dust in 2020|url=http://news.sciencemag.org/scienceinsider/2011/05/nasa-aims-to-grab-asteroid-dust.html|newspaper=Science Magazine|date=26 May 2011|access-date=26 May 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110529114319/http://news.sciencemag.org/scienceinsider/2011/05/nasa-aims-to-grab-asteroid-dust.html|archive-date=29 May 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> not including the [[Atlas V]] launch vehicle, which is about {{US$|183.5 million}}.<ref name=\"aug2013release\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nasa.gov/press/2013/august/nasa-selects-launch-services-contract-for-osiris-rex-mission/|title=NASA Selects Launch Services Contract for OSIRIS-REx Mission|last1=Buck|first1=Joshua |last2=Diller|first2=George|publisher=[[NASA]]|date=5 August 2013|accessdate=8 September 2013}}</ref> It is the third planetary science mission selected in the [[New Frontiers program]], after [[Juno (spacecraft)|''Juno'']] and ''[[New Horizons]]''. The [[principal investigator]] is [[Dante Lauretta]] from the [[University of Arizona]].\n\n==Mission==\n[[File:Asteroid-Bennu-OSIRIS-RExArrival-GifAnimation-20181203.gif|thumb|left|Asteroid Bennu, imaged by the OSIRIS-REx probe<br />(3 December 2018)]]\nOverall management, engineering and navigation for the mission is provided by [[NASA]]{{'s}} [[Goddard Space Flight Center]], while the [[University of Arizona]]{{'s}} [[Lunar and Planetary Laboratory]] provides principal science operations and [[Lockheed Martin Space Systems]] built the spacecraft and provides mission operations.<ref name=\"press kit\" /> The science team includes members from the United States, [[Canada]], [[France]], [[Germany]], [[United Kingdom]], and [[Italy]].<ref name=\"eoportal\">{{cite web |url=https://directory.eoportal.org/web/eoportal/satellite-missions/o/osiris-rex |title=OSIRIS-REx |work=Earth Observation Portal Directory |last=Kramer |first=Herbert J. |accessdate=20 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter traveling for approximately two years, the spacecraft [[Space rendezvous|rendezvoused]] with asteroid [[101955 Bennu]] in December 2018<ref name=nasa-20170109>{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/feature/goddard/2017/nasa-selects-participating-scientists-for-mission-to-asteroid-bennu|title=NASA Selects Participating Scientists for Mission to Asteroid Bennu|publisher=NASA |last=Hille|first=Karl|date=9 January 2018|accessdate=2 February 2018}}</ref> and began 505 days of surface mapping at a distance of approximately {{convert|5|km|mi}}.<ref name=\"pressrelease\"/> Results of that mapping will be used by the mission team to select the site from which to take a sample of the asteroid's surface.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.borntoengineer.com/nasa-successfully-launch-osiris-rex-asteroid-mission/|title=NASA Successfully Launch OSIRIS-REx Asteroid Mission|work=borntoengineer.com|date=9 September 2016|accessdate=9 September 2016}}</ref> Then a close approach (without landing) will be attempted to allow extension of a robotic arm to gather the sample.<ref>{{cite news|title=UA gets $1.2M to aid in asteroid mission|url=http://tucsoncitizen.com/morgue/2006/10/31/31046-ua-gets-1-2m-to-aid-in-asteroid-mission/|newspaper=Tucson Citizen|date=26 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nAn asteroid was chosen as the target of study because an asteroid is a \"[[time capsule]]\" from the birth of our [[Solar System]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.space.com/34007-nasa-launches-osiris-rex-asteroid-sampling-mission.html|title=Next Stop, Bennu! NASA Launches Bold Asteroid-Sampling Mission|work=Space.com|first=Mike|last=Wall|date=8 September 2016}}</ref> In particular, [[101955 Bennu]] was selected because of the availability of pristine [[carbonaceous]] material, a key element in [[Organic compound|organic molecules]] necessary for life as well as representative of matter from before the formation of Earth. Organic molecules, such as [[amino acid]]s, have previously been found in meteorite and comet samples, indicating that some ingredients necessary for life can be naturally synthesized in outer space.<ref name=pressrelease/>\n\n[[File:To Bennu and Back.webm|thumb|right|250px|OSIRIS-REx mission overview video]]\n\nFollowing a collection of material (60 grams), the sample will be returned to Earth in a {{convert|46|kg}} capsule similar to that which returned the samples of a comet [[81P/Wild]] on the [[Stardust (spacecraft)|Stardust spacecraft]]. The return trip to Earth will be shorter and the capsule will land with a parachute at the [[Utah Test and Training Range]] in September 2023 before being transported to the [[Johnson Space Center]] for processing in a dedicated research facility.<ref name=pressrelease/>\n\n===Launch===\n{{multiple image |align=right |direction=vertical |width=250\n |image1=Liftoff-of-OSIRIS-REx.ogg |caption1=OSIRIS-REx launch video\n |image2=Animation of OSIRIS-REx trajectory.gif |caption2=Animation of OSIRIS-REx{{'s}} trajectory from {{nowrap|9 September 2016}} to {{nowrap|3 December 2018}} <br /> {{legend2|magenta|OSIRIS-REx}}{{\u00b7}}{{legend2|lime|[[101955 Bennu]]}}{{\u00b7}}{{legend2|blue|Earth}}\n |image3=Animation of OSIRIS-Rex trajectory around 101955 Bennu.gif |caption3=Animation of OSIRIS-REx{{'s}} trajectory around [[101955 Bennu]] from {{nowrap|25 December 2018}}<br /> {{legend2|magenta|OSIRIS-REx}}{{\u00b7}}{{legend2|lime|101955 Bennu}}\n}}\n\nThe launch was on 8 September 2016 at 23:05 [[UTC]] on a [[United Launch Alliance]] [[Atlas V]] 411 from [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station|Cape Canaveral]], [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station Space Launch Complex 41|Space Launch Complex 41]].<ref name=\"nasasf20160908\"/> The 411 rocket configuration consists of a [[RD-180]] powered first stage with a single [[AJ-60A]] solid fuel booster, and a [[Centaur (rocket stage)|Centaur]] upper stage.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2016/09/atlas-v-osiris-rexs-round-trip-asteroid-bennu/|title=Atlas V begins OSIRIS-REx's round trip to the asteroid Bennu|work=[[NASASpaceFlight.com]]|first=William|last=Graham|date=8 September 2016}}</ref> OSIRIS-REx separated from the launch vehicle 55 minutes after ignition.<ref name=\"press kit\"/> The launch was declared \"exactly perfect\" by the mission's Principal Investigator, with no anomalies worked before or during launch.<ref name=\"exactlyperfect\">{{cite news|last1=Wall|first1=Mike|title='Exactly Perfect'! NASA Hails Asteroid Sample-Return Mission's Launch|url=http://www.space.com/34020-nasa-hails-osiris-rex-asteroid-mission-launch.html|work=Space.com|accessdate=10 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Cruise===\nOSIRIS-REx entered the cruise phase shortly after separation from the launch vehicle, following successful solar panel deployment, propulsion system initiation, and establishment of a communication link with Earth.<ref name=\"exactlyperfect\"/> Its hyperbolic escape speed from Earth was about {{convert|5.41|km/s|mi/s|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=OSIRIS-REx Mission & Trajectory Design|url=http://spaceflight101.com/osiris-rex/osiris-rex-mission-profile/|website=Spaceflight101.com|date=Sep 2016}}</ref> On 28 December 2016, the spacecraft successfully performed its first deep space maneuver to change its velocity by {{convert|431|m/s|km/h mph|abbr=on}} using {{convert|354|kg|lb|abbr=on}} of fuel.<ref name=\"nasa20170117\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/feature/goddard/2017/successful-deep-space-maneuver-for-nasa-s-osiris-rex-spacecraft |title=Successful Deep Space Maneuver for NASA's OSIRIS-REx Spacecraft |publisher=NASA |first=Nancy |last=Neal-Jones |date=17 January 2017 |accessdate=7 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"sfnow20170201\">{{cite news |url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2017/02/01/nasas-osiris-rex-probe-moonlights-as-asteroid-sleuth/ |title=NASA's OSIRIS-REx probe moonlights as asteroid sleuth |work=Spaceflight Now |first=Stephen |last=Clark |date=1 February 2017 |accessdate=9 March 2017}}</ref> An additional, smaller firing of its thrusters on 18 January further refined its course for an Earth [[gravity assist]] on 22 September 2017.<ref name=\"nasa20170117\" /> The cruise phase lasted until its encounter with Bennu in December 2018,<ref name=nasa-20170109 /> after which it entered its science and sample collection phase.<ref name=\"nasa20170117\" />\n\nDuring its cruise phase, OSIRIS-REx was used to search for a class of [[near-Earth object]]s known as [[Earth trojan|Earth-Trojan asteroids]] as it passed through Sun\u2013Earth {{L4}} Lagrange point. Between 9 and 20 February 2017, the OSIRIS-REx team used the spacecraft's MapCam camera to search for the objects, taking about 135 survey images each day for processing by scientists at the [[University of Arizona]]. The search was beneficial even though no new trojans were found,<ref name=\"trojanresults\">{{cite web|title=OSIRIS-REx Asteroid Search Tests Instruments|url=http://www.asteroidmission.org/?latest-news=osiris-rex-asteroid-search-tests-instruments-science-team|publisher=[[NASA]]|access-date=2018-12-20}}</ref> as it closely resembled the operation required as the spacecraft approached Bennu, searching for natural satellites and other potential hazards.<ref name=\"sfnow20170201\" /><ref name=\"nasa20170209\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/feature/goddard/2017/osiris-rex-begins-earth-trojan-asteroid-search |title=NASA's OSIRIS-REx Begins Earth-Trojan Asteroid Search |publisher=NASA |first1=Erin |last1=Morton |first2=Nancy |last2=Neal-Jones |date=9 February 2017 |accessdate=9 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 February 2017, while {{convert|673|e6km|e6mi|abbr=unit}} from [[Jupiter]], the PolyCam instrument aboard OSIRIS-REx successfully imaged the giant planet and three of its moons, [[Callisto (moon)|Callisto]], [[Io (moon)|Io]], and [[Ganymede (moon)|Ganymede]].<ref name=\"nasa20170215\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/image-feature/goddard/2017/osiris-rex-takes-closer-image-of-jupiter |title=NASA's OSIRIS-REx Takes Closer Image of Jupiter |publisher=NASA |date=15 February 2017 |accessdate=9 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nOSIRIS-REx flew by Earth on 22 September 2017.\n\n===Arrival and survey===\nOn 3 December 2018, NASA affirmed that OSIRIS-REx had matched the speed and orbit of Bennu at a distance of about {{convert|19|km|mi|sp=us}}, effectively reaching the asteroid. OSIRIS-REx performed closer passes of the Bennu surface, initially at about {{convert|6.5|km|mi|abbr=on}} through December to further refine the shape and orbit of Bennu. Preliminary spectroscopic surveys of the asteroid's surface by OSIRIS-REx spacecraft, detected the presence of [[Mineral hydration|hydrated minerals]] in the form of [[clay]]. While researchers suspect that Bennu was too small to host water, the hydroxyl groups may have come from water presence in its parent body before Bennu split off.<ref>{{cite web |title=NASA's Newly Arrived OSIRIS-REx Spacecraft Already Discovers Water on Asteroid |date=11 December 2018 |publisher=NASA |url=https://www.nasa.gov/press-release/nasa-s-newly-arrived-osiris-rex-spacecraft-already-discovers-water-on-asteroid}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2018/12/181210150554.htm  |title = Water found on asteroid, confirming Bennu as excellent mission target | date = 10 December 2018 | accessdate = 10 December 2018 | work = [[Science Daily]] }}</ref>\n\nOSIRIS-REx entered orbit around Bennu on 31 December 2018 at about {{convert|1.75|km|mi|abbr=on}} to start its extensive remote mapping and sensing campaign for the selection of a sample site. This is the closest distance that any spacecraft has orbited a celestial object, surpassing the [[Rosetta (spacecraft)|''Rosetta'']]{{'s}} orbit of comet [[67P/Churyumov\u2013Gerasimenko]] at {{convert|7|km|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"NYT-20181203\">{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/03/science/osiris-rex-bennu-asteroid-arrival.html | title= NASA's Osiris-Rex Arrives at Asteroid Bennu After a Two-Year Journey | first=  Kenneth | last = Chang | date = 3 December 2018 | accessdate = 3 December 2018 | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url = https://solarsystem.nasa.gov/news/805/nasas-osiris-rex-spacecraft-enters-close-orbit-around-bennu-breaking-record/ | title = NASA's OSIRIS-REx Spacecraft Enters Close Orbit Around Bennu, Breaking Record | first= Eric | last=  Morten | date = 31 December 2018 | accessdate = 1 January 2019 | publisher = [[NASA]] }}</ref> At this altitude, it takes the spacecraft 62 hours to orbit Bennu.<ref>[https://www.asteroidmission.org/?latest-news=nasas-osiris-rex-spacecraft-enters-close-orbit-around-bennu-breaking-record NASA's OSIRIS-REx Spacecraft Enters Close Orbit Around Bennu, Breaking Record]. Lonnie Shekhtman, OSIRIS-Rex Mission home page. 31 December 2018.</ref> At the end of this detailed survey, the spacecraft will enter a closer orbit with a radius of {{cvt|1|km|abbr=on}}.<ref>[https://www.asteroidmission.org/asteroid-operations/#detailedsurveybaseballdiamond Orbital B Phase. Osiris-Rex.] Accessed on 22 March 2018.</ref>\n\n===Sample acquisition===\n[[File:Artist's concept of OSIRIS-REx TAGSAM in operation.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Artist's concept of TAGSAM instrument in operation]]\nRehearsals will be performed before the sampling event, during which the solar arrays will be raised into a Y-shaped configuration to minimize the chance of dust accumulation during contact and provide more ground clearance in case the spacecraft tips over (up to 45\u00b0) during contact.<ref name=\"eoportal\"/> The descent will be very slow to minimize thruster firings prior to contact in order to reduce the likelihood of asteroid surface contamination by unreacted [[hydrazine]] propellant. Contact with the surface of Bennu will be detected using accelerometers, and the impact force will be dissipated by a spring in the TAGSAM arm.\n\nUpon surface contact by the TAGSAM instrument, a burst of [[nitrogen]] gas will be released, which will blow [[regolith]] particles smaller than {{convert|2|cm|in|1|abbr=on}} into the sampler head at the end of the robotic arm. A five-second timer will limit collection time to mitigate the chance of a collision. After the timer expires, the back-away maneuver will initiate a safe departure from the asteroid.<ref name=\"eoportal\"/>\n\nOSIRIS-REx will then halt the drift away from the asteroid in case it is necessary to return for another sampling attempt. The spacecraft will use images and spinning maneuvers to verify the sample has been acquired as well as determine its mass and verify it is in excess of the required {{convert|60|g|oz|1}}.<ref name=\"eoportal\"/> In the event of a failed sampling attempt, the spacecraft will return for another try. There is enough nitrogen gas for three attempts.<ref name=\"press kit\"/>\n\nIn addition to the bulk sampling mechanism, contact pads on the end of the sampling head will passively collect dust grains smaller than {{val|1|u=mm}}, upon contact with the asteroid. These pads are made from tiny loops of stainless steel.<ref name=\"DSLAURETTA\">{{cite web |url=https://dslauretta.com/2014/02/05/riding-the-vomit-comet/ |title=How Do We know When We Have Collected a Sample of Bennu? |website=Dslauretta.com |last=Lauretta |first=Dante |accessdate=23 August 2016|date=5 February 2014 }}</ref>\n\nAfter the sampling attempt, the Sample-Return Capsule (SRC) lid will be opened to allow the sampler head to be stowed. The arm will then be retracted into its launch configuration, and the SRC lid will be closed and latched preparing to return to [[Earth]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://spaceflight101.com/osiris-rex/osiris-rex-sample-return-capsule/ |title=Sample Return Capsule |work=Spaceflight101.com |accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:OSIRIS-REx candidate sample sites on Bennu.png|thumb|center|800px|The final four candidate sample sites]]\n\nNASA selected the final four candidate sample sites in August 2019, named Nightingale, Kingfisher, Osprey, and Sandpiper.<ref name=\"final four sample sites\">{{cite press release |title=NASA Mission Selects Final Four Site Candidates for Asteroid Sample Return |url=https://www.nasa.gov/press-release/nasa-mission-selects-final-four-site-candidates-for-asteroid-sample-return|agency= [[NASA]]|date= 2019-09-12|access-date=2019-12-28}}</ref> On December 12, 2019, they announced that Nightingale had been selected as the primary sample site and Osprey was selected as the backup site.<ref name=\"site-selected\">{{cite press release |title=X Marks the Spot: Sample Site Nightingale Targeted for Touchdown |url= https://www.asteroidmission.org/?latest-news=x-marks-the-spot-nasa-selects-site-for-asteroid-sample-collection |publisher=AsteroidMission.org |agency= [[NASA]]|date= 2019-12-12|access-date=2019-12-28}}</ref> Both located within craters, Nightingale is near Bennu's north pole while Osprey is near the equator. NASA plans to perform the actual sampling in late August, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.universetoday.com/145295/osiris-rex-did-its-closest-flyover-yet-just-250-meters-above-its-sample-site/|title=OSIRIS-REx did its Closest Flyover Yet, just 250 Meters Above its Sample Site|last=Gough|first=Evan|date=2020-03-09|website=Universe Today|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref>\n\n[[File:OSIRIS-REx Checkpoint Rehearsal.gif|thumb|The April 2020 sample collection rehearsal that brought OSIRIS-REx {{cvt|65|m}} from the surface. In this series of SamCam images the [[TAGSAM]] head is in the center and the Nightingale sample site comes in to view at the top of the frame at the end.]]\n\nOn April 15, 2020, a sample collection rehearsal was successfully coordinated over the Nightingale sample site. The exercise took OSIRIS-REx as close as {{convert|65|m}} from the surface before performing a back-away burn.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://phys.org/news/2020-04-closer-asteroid-bennu.html|title=One step closer to touching asteroid Bennu|last=Morton|first=Erin|date=April 16, 2020|website=Phys.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=OSIRIS-REx Buzzes Sample Site Nightingale|date=14 April 2020|url=https://www.asteroidmission.org/checkpoint-rehearsal-movie/|website=AsteroidMission.org|publisher=[[NASA]]|access-date= 16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Curation===\nOn 24 September 2023, the OSIRIS-REx return capsule will re-enter Earth's atmosphere and land under a parachute at the Air Force's [[Utah Test and Training Range]].<ref name=\"planetary20180705\">{{cite web |url=http://www.planetary.org/blogs/jason-davis/why-sample-return.html|title=What's the benefit of sample return?|publisher=The Planetary Society|first=Jason|last=Davis|date=5 July 2018|accessdate=2 September 2018}}</ref> The sample will be [[Extraterrestrial sample curation|curated]] at NASA's [[Astromaterials Research and Exploration Science Directorate]] (ARES) and at Japan's [[Extraterrestrial Sample Curation Center]].<ref name=\"planetary20180705\"/><ref name=\"jaxa-cur\">{{cite web|url=https://curation.isas.jaxa.jp/curation/osiris/index.html|title=OSIRIS-REx Project|publisher=JAXA/Astromaterial Science Research Group |accessdate=2 September 2018}}</ref> The sample material from the asteroid will be distributed to requesting organisations worldwide by ARES.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ares.jsc.nasa.gov/missions/osiris-rex/ |title=OSIRIS-REx|publisher=NASA/Astromaterials Research & Exploration Science Directorate|accessdate=2 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Name==\nOSIRIS-REx is an acronym, and each letter or combination of letters relates to part of the project:<ref name=\"asteroidmission.org\">[https://www.asteroidmission.org/objectives/osiris-rex-acronym/]</ref>\n\n*O \u2013 '''O'''rigins\n*SI \u2013 '''S'''pectral '''I'''nterpretation'''\n*RI \u2013 '''R'''esource '''I'''dentification\n*S \u2013 '''S'''ecurity\n*REx \u2013 '''R'''egolith '''Ex'''plorer\n\nEach of these words was chosen to represent an aspect of this mission.<ref name=\"asteroidmission.org\"/> For example, the S, for security means the security of Earth from hazardous NEO.<ref name=\"asteroidmission.org\"/> Specifically it refers to better understanding the [[Yarkovsky Effect]], that changes the trajectory of the asteroid.<ref name=\"asteroidmission.org\"/> Regolith Explorer means that the mission will study the texture, morphology, geochemistry, and spectral properties of the regolith of asteroid Bennu.<ref name=\"asteroidmission.org\"/>\n\nWhen its heritage concept was proposed in the Discovery program in 2004, it was called OSIRIS without the additional REx.<ref name=\"sci.esa.int\">[http://sci.esa.int/Conferences/MarcoPolo-ws08/The_OSIRIS_mission_-_Dante_Lauretta.pdf]</ref> This mission is also sometimes called New Frontiers 3, for it being the third of the New Frontiers program missions.<ref name=\"sci.esa.int\"/><ref>[https://supplychain.gsfc.nasa.gov/sites/supplychain/files/docs/2016/R.%20Perison%20-%20J.%20Dworkin%20-%20SC%202016.pdf]</ref>\n\nThe acronym OSIRIS was chosen in reference to the ancient mythological Egyptian god [[Osiris]], the underworld lord of the dead. He was classically depicted as a green-skinned man with a pharaoh's beard, partially mummy-wrapped at the legs and wearing a distinctive crown with two large ostrich feathers at either side.<ref name='NASAcronyms'>{{cite news|url=http://www.livescience.com/33309-nasa-acronyms-osiris-rex-asteroid-spacecraft-mission.html|title=NASAcronyms: How OSIRIS-REx Got Its Name|last=Wolchover|first=Natalie|work=LiveScience|date=27 May 2011|accessdate=12 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.space.com/11802-nasa-asteroid-mission-dangerous-1999-rq36.html|title=Why NASA Chose Potentially Threatening Asteroid for New Mission|last=Moskowitz|first=Clara|work=Space.com|date=27 May 2011 |accessdate=14 May 2017}}</ref> Rex means \"king\" in Latin. His name was chosen for this mission as [[101955 Bennu|asteroid Bennu]] is a threatening [[Impact event|Earth impactor]], with an estimated 1-in-1800 chance of hitting Earth in the year 2170.<ref name='NASAcronyms'/>\n\n==Science objectives==\n[[File:OSIRIS-REx StowCam first light.jpeg|thumb|Sample-return capsule as seen by StowCam]]\nThe science objectives of the mission are:<ref>[http://osiris-rex.lpl.arizona.edu/downloads/OSIRIS_REx_infosheet.pdf OSIRIS-Rex Infosheet] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120417120453/http://osiris-rex.lpl.arizona.edu/downloads/OSIRIS_REx_infosheet.pdf |date=17 April 2012 }} (PDF)</ref>\n#Return and analyze a sample of pristine [[C-type asteroid|carbonaceous asteroid]] regolith in an amount sufficient to study the nature, history, and distribution of its constituent minerals and [[organic compound]]s.\n#Map the global properties, chemistry, and mineralogy of a primitive carbonaceous asteroid to characterize its geologic and dynamic history and provide context for the returned samples.\n#Document the texture, morphology, geochemistry, and [[Spectroscopy|spectral properties]] of the regolith at the sampling site ''in situ'' at scales down to millimeters.\n#Measure the [[Yarkovsky effect]] (a thermal force on the object) on a potentially hazardous asteroid and constrain the asteroid properties that contribute to this effect.\n#Characterize the integrated global properties of a primitive carbonaceous asteroid to allow for direct comparison with ground-based telescopic data of the entire asteroid population.\n\n<!--I see no use for an old model of it shape when we have real images now. [[File:Bennu shape model.gif|thumb|right|Shape model of the mission's destination, asteroid Bennu]]-->\nTelescopic observations have helped define the orbit of [[101955 Bennu]], a [[near-Earth object]] with a mean diameter in the range of {{convert|480|to|511|m|ft|sp=us}}.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Physical properties of OSIRIS-REx target asteroid {{mp|101955|1999 RQ|36}}. Derived from Herschel, VLT/ VISIR, and Spitzer observations |journal=Astronomy & Astrophysics |first1=T. G. |last1=M\u00fcller |first2=L. |last2=O'Rourke |first3=A. M. |last3=Barucci |first4=A. |last4=P\u00e1l |first5=C. |last5=Kiss |first6=P. |last6=Zeidler |first7=B. |last7=Altieri |first8=B. M. |last8=Gonz\u00e1lez-Garc\u00eda |first9=M. |last9=K\u00fcppers |volume=548 |at=A36 |date=December 2012 |doi=10.1051/0004-6361/201220066 |bibcode=2012A&A...548A..36M |arxiv=1210.5370}}</ref> It completes an orbit of the [[Sun]] every 436.604 days (1.2 years). This orbit takes it close to the Earth every six years. Although the orbit is reasonably well known, scientists continue to refine it. It is critical to know the orbit of Bennu because recent calculations produced a cumulative probability of 1 in 1410 (or 0.071%) of impact with Earth in the period 2169 to 2199.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://neo.jpl.nasa.gov/risk/a101955.html |title=Earth Impact Risk Summary for 101955 Bennu |accessdate=29 April 2013 |date=5 August 2010 |work=Near Earth Object Program |publisher=NASA's JPL}}</ref> One of the mission objectives is to refine understanding of non-gravitational effects (such as the [[Yarkovsky effect]]) on this orbit, and the implications of those effects for Bennu's collision probability. Knowing Bennu's physical properties will be critical for future scientists to understand when developing an [[asteroid impact avoidance]] mission.<ref name=\"asteroidmission\">{{cite web |url=http://www.asteroidmission.org/mission/ |title=OSIRIS-REx - The Mission |work=Asteroidmission.org}}</ref>\n\nTelescopic observations have revealed some basic properties of Bennu. They indicate that it is very dark and is classified as a [[B-type asteroid]], a sub-type of the carbonaceous [[C-type asteroid]]s. Such asteroids are considered \"primitive\", having undergone little geological change from their time of formation.\n{{clear}}\n\n==Specifications==\n{{multiple image |direction=vertical |align=right |total_width=200\n |image1=OSIRIS-REx.stl |caption1=3D model of OSIRIS-REx\n |image2=OSIRIS-REx instrument deck.png |caption2=OSIRIS-REx instrument deck\n}}\n* Dimensions: Length {{convert|8|ft|m|1|order=flip|abbr=on}}, width {{convert|8|ft|m|1|order=flip|abbr=on}}, height {{convert|10.33|ft|m|1|order=flip|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"press kit\" />\n* Width with [[Solar panels on spacecraft|solar arrays]] deployed: {{convert|20.25|ft|m|1|order=flip|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"press kit\" />\n* Power: Two solar arrays generate {{val|1226|-|3000|u=watts}}, depending on the spacecraft's distance from the Sun. Energy is stored in [[Li-ion]] batteries.<ref name=\"press kit\" />\n* Propulsion system: Based on a [[hydrazine]] monopropellant system developed for the ''[[Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter]]'', carrying {{convert|2710|lb|kg|order=flip|abbr=on}} of propellant and helium.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dslauretta.com/2014/12/16/integration-of-the-osiris-rex-main-propellant-tank/ |title=Integration of the OSIRIS-REx Main Propellant Tank |website=Dslauretta.com |first=Dante |last=Lauretta |date=16 December 2014 |accessdate=20 April 2015}}</ref>\n* The Sample-Return Capsule (SRC) will re-enter the Earth's atmosphere for a parachute assisted landing. The capsule with encased samples will be retrieved from Earth's surface and studied, as was done with the ''[[Stardust (spacecraft)|Stardust]]'' mission.\n\n==Payload==\nIn addition to its telecommunication equipment, the spacecraft will carry a suite of instruments that will study the asteroid in many wavelengths,<ref name=\"instruments\" /> as well as image the asteroid, and retrieve a physical sample to return to Earth. [[The Planetary Society]] coordinated a campaign to invite interested persons to have their names or artwork on the mission's spirit of exploration saved on a microchip now carried in the spacecraft.<ref>\n*{{cite news |url=http://www.asteroidmission.org/?latest-news=nasa-invites-public-send-artwork-asteroid |title=NASA Invites Public to Send Artwork to an Asteroid |publisher=University of Arizona |date=19 February 2016 |accessdate=1 April 2016}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.planetary.org/get-involved/messages/bennu/ |title=OSIRIS-REx: Messages to Bennu! |publisher=The Planetary Society |accessdate=10 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n===OCAMS===\n[[File:Osiris-Rex Ocams 007.jpg|thumb|Imaging camera suite]]\nThe OSIRIS-REx Camera Suite (OCAMS) consists of the PolyCam, the MapCam, and the SamCam.<ref name=\"instruments\">{{cite web |url=http://www.asteroidmission.org/objectives/instruments/ |title=Instruments: Science Payload |publisher=University of Arizona |accessdate=18 September 2016}}</ref> Together they acquire information on asteroid Bennu by providing global mapping, sample site reconnaissance and characterization, high-resolution imaging, and records of the sample acquisition.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://dslauretta.com/2014/01/11/ocams-the-eyes-of-osiris-rex/ |title=OCAMS \u2013 The Eyes of OSIRIS-REx |website=Dslauretta.com |first=Dante |last=Lauretta |date=11 January 2014 |accessdate=10 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n*PolyCam, an {{convert|8|in|cm|adj=on}} telescope, acquires images with increasingly higher resolution as the spacecraft approaches the asteroid.\n*MapCam searches for satellites and outgassing plumes. It maps the asteroid in 4 different colors, informs the model of Bennu's shape and provides high resolution imaging of the potential sample sites.\n*SamCam continuously documents the sample acquisitions.\n\n===OLA===\nThe OSIRIS-REx Laser Altimeter (OLA) is a scanning and [[LIDAR]] instrument that will provide high resolution topographical information throughout the mission.<ref name=\"instruments\" /> The information received by OLA creates global [[topographic]] maps of Bennu, local maps of candidate sample sites, ranging in support of other instruments, and support navigation and gravity analyses.\n\nOLA scans the surface of Bennu at specific intervals to rapidly map the entire surface of the asteroid to achieve its primary objective of producing local and global topographic maps. The data collected by OLA will also be used to develop a control network relative to the center of mass of the asteroid and to enhance and refine gravitational studies of Bennu.\n\nOLA has a single common receiver and two complementary transmitter assemblies that enhance the resolution of the information brought back. OLA's high-energy laser transmitter is used for ranging and mapping from {{convert|1|to|7.5|km|mi|1|abbr=on}}. The low-energy transmitter is used for ranging and imaging from {{convert|0.5|to|1|km|mi|1|abbr=on}}. The repetition rate of these transmitters sets the data acquisition rate of OLA. Laser pulses from both the low and high energy transmitters are directed onto a movable scanning mirror, which is co-aligned with the field of view of the receiver telescope limiting the effects of background solar radiation. Each pulse provides target range, azimuth, elevation, received intensity and a time-tag.\n\nOLA was funded by the [[Canadian Space Agency]] (CSA) and was built by [[MacDonald, Dettwiler and Associates]] at Brampton, Ontario, Canada.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.asc-csa.gc.ca/eng/satellites/osiris-rex/ola.asp |title=OLA, Canada's Contribution to OSIRIS-REx |work=Canadian Space Agency |date=4 March 2013 |accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref> OLA was delivered for integration with the spacecraft on 17 November 2015.<ref>\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/content/goddard/canada-contributes-to-nasa-s-osiris-rex-mission |title=Canada Contributes to NASA's OSIRIS-REx Mission |publisher=NASA |first=Nancy N. |last=Jones |date=17 July 2014}}\n*{{cite news |url=https://www.kelownanow.com/news/news/National_News/15/12/17/Canada_to_Invest_in_Space_Exploration_with_New_Laser/ |title=Canada to Invest in Space Exploration with New Laser |work=Kelowna Now |first=Cassandra |last=Jeffery |date=17 December 2015}}</ref> The lead instrument scientist of OLA is Michael Daly from [[York University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asc-csa.gc.ca/eng/satellites/osiris-rex/canadas-role.asp|title=Canada's role in OSIRIS-REx|date=4 March 2013|website=www.asc-csa.gc.ca|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\n===OVIRS===\n[[File:Osiris-Rex Ovirs gsfc 20150619 2015-12655 019-023.jpg|thumb|OVIRS]]\nThe OSIRIS-REx Visible and IR Spectrometer (OVIRS) is a [[spectrometer]], which measures light to provide mineral and organic spectral maps and local spectral information of candidate sample sites.<ref name=\"instruments\" /> It also provides full-disc asteroid spectral data, global spectral maps (20&nbsp;m resolution), and spectra of the sample site (blue to near-infrared, {{nowrap|400\u20134,300 nm}}, with a [[spectral resolution]] of {{nowrap|7.5\u201322 nm}}).<ref name=\"simonmiller2013\">{{cite conference |url=http://www.lpi.usra.edu/meetings/lpsc2013/pdf/1100.pdf |title=OSIRIS-REx OVIRS: A Scalable Visible to Near-IR Spectrometer for Planetary Study |conference=44th Lunar and Planetary Science Conference. 18\u201322 March 2013. The Woodlands, Texas. |first1=A. A. |last1=Simon-Miller |first2=D. C. |last2=Reuter |date=2013 |bibcode=2013LPI....44.1100S}}</ref> These data will be used in concert with OTES spectra to guide sample-site selection. These spectral ranges and resolving powers are sufficient to provide surface maps of mineralogical and molecular components including [[carbonate]]s, [[silicate]]s, [[sulfate]]s, [[oxide]]s, [[Adsorption#Adsorbed water|adsorbed water]] and a wide range of [[organic compound]]s. It provides at least two spectral samples per resolution [[Chemical element|element]] taking full advantage of the spectral resolution.{{Clarify|reason=What does this sentence mean?|date=January 2020}}\n\n===OTES===\n[[File:Osiris-Rex Otes-3.jpg|thumb|right|OTES]]\nThe OSIRIS-REx Thermal Emission Spectrometer (OTES) provides mineral and [[thermal infrared spectroscopy|thermal emission spectral]] maps and local spectral information of candidate sample sites by collecting [[Infrared spectroscopy|thermal infrared]] data from 4\u201350&nbsp;\u00b5m.<ref name=\"instruments\" />\n\nOTES provides full-disc Bennu spectral data, global spectral maps, and local sample site spectral information used to characterize the global, regional, and local mineralogic composition and thermal emission from the asteroid surface. The [[wavelength]] range, spectral resolution, and radiometric performance are sufficient to resolve and identify the key vibrational absorption features of silicate, carbonate, sulfate, phosphate, oxide, and hydroxide minerals. OTES is also used to measure the total thermal emission from Bennu in support of the requirement to measure emitted radiation globally. Based on the performance of [[Mini-TES]] in the dusty surface environment of Mars, OTES was designed to be resilient to extreme dust contamination on the optical elements.\n\n===REXIS===\nThe Regolith X-ray Imaging Spectrometer (REXIS) will provide an [[X-ray spectroscopy]] map of Bennu to constrain the element abundances. It complements core OSIRIS-REx mission science.<ref name=\"instruments\" /> REXIS is a collaborative development by four groups within [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (MIT) and [[Harvard University]], with the potential to involve more than 100 students throughout the process. REXIS is based on flight heritage hardware, thereby minimizing elements of technical risk, schedule risk, and cost risk.\n\nREXIS is a [[coded aperture]] soft X-ray (0.3\u20137.5&nbsp;keV) telescope that images X-ray fluorescence line emission produced by the interaction of solar [[X-rays]] and the [[solar wind]] with the regolith of Bennu. Images are formed with 21 [[Minute of arc|arcminute]] resolution (4.3&nbsp;m spatial resolution at a distance of 700&nbsp;m). Imaging is achieved by correlating the detected X-ray image with a 64 x 64 element random mask (1.536&nbsp;mm pixels). REXIS will store each X-ray event data in order to maximize the data storage usage and to minimize the risk. The [[pixel]]s will be addressed in 64 x 64 bins and the 0.3\u20137.5&nbsp;keV range will be covered by five broad bands and 11 narrow line bands. A 24&nbsp;s resolution time tag will be interleaved with the event data to account for Bennu rotation. Images will be reconstructed on the ground after downlink of the event list. Images are formed simultaneously in 16 energy bands centered on the dominant lines of abundant surface elements from O-K (0.5&nbsp;keV) to Fe-K\u00df (7&nbsp;keV) as well the representative continuum. During orbital phase 5B, a 21-day orbit 700&nbsp;m from the surface of Bennu, a total of at least 133 events/asteroid pixel/energy band are expected under 2&nbsp;keV; enough to obtain significant constraints on element abundances at scales larger than 10&nbsp;m.\n\nOn 11 November 2019, university students and researchers involved in the mission accidentally discovered X-ray burst from a [[black hole]] name MAXI J0637-430 locate 30,000 light-years away, during observing the asteroid with REXIS.<ref>{{cite web| title = OSIRIS-REx Observes a Black Hole\n | date = 3 March 2020| publisher = NASA Goddard | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Erry315AwmI | access-date = 5 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===TAGSAM===\n[[File:Osiris-Rex Sample-return-arm-test-167.jpg|thumb|TAGSAM arm test before launch]]\n{{main|TAGSAM}}\nThe sample-return system, called Touch-And-Go Sample Acquisition Mechanism (TAGSAM), consists of a sampler head with an articulated {{convert|3.35|m|ft|0|adj=on|sp=us}} arm.<ref name=\"press kit\" /><ref name=\"instruments\" /> An on-board nitrogen source will support up to three separate sampling attempts for a minimum total amount of {{convert|60|g}} of sample. The surface contact pads will also collect fine-grained material.\n\nHighlights of the TAGSAM instrument and technique include:\n* Slowly approach surface at {{convert|0.2|m/s|sp=us}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://dslauretta.com/2013/11/27/how-to-get-to-bennu-and-back/ |title=How To Get To Bennu and Back |website=Dslauretta.com |first=Dante |last=Lauretta |date=27 November 2013 |accessdate=10 September 2016}}</ref>\n* Contact within {{convert|25|m|sp=us}} of selected location\n* OCAMS documents sampling at 1&nbsp;Hz\n* Collect samples in less than five seconds, direct nitrogen (N<sub>2</sub>) annular jet fluidizes regolith, surface-contact pad captures surface sample\n* Verify bulk sample collection via spacecraft inertia change; surface sample by imaging sampler head\n* Sampler head stored in Sample-Return Capsule (SRC) and returned to Earth\n{{clear}}\n\n== Cooperation with JAXA ==\n[[Hayabusa2]] is a similar mission from [[JAXA]] to collect a sample from near-Earth asteroid [[162173 Ryugu]]. It arrived at the asteroid in June 2018 and left in November 2019 after two successful sample collections. Due to the similarity and overlapping timelines of the two missions, NASA and JAXA signed an agreement to collaborate on sample exchange and research.<ref>{{cite web |title= NASA, JAXA reach asteroid sample-sharing agreement | first1 = Stephen | last1 = Clark | publisher = Spaceflight Now| date= 15 December 2014|url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2014/12/15/nasa-jaxa-reach-asteroid-sample-sharing-agreement/|access-date = 12 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title = NASA, Curation Preparation for Ryugu Sample Returned by JAXA's Hayabusa2 Mission|publisher = [[NASA]] |first1=Keiko |last1=Nakamura-Messenger |first2 = Kevin |last2 = Righter | first3  = Christopher | last3 = Snead | first4 = Francis | last4 = McCubbin | first5 = Lisa | last5 =  Pace | first6 = Ryan | last6 = Zeigler | first7 = Cindy | last7 = Evans| year = 2017| url = https://ntrs.nasa.gov/archive/nasa/casi.ntrs.nasa.gov/20170008918.pdf|access-date = 12 February 2020}}</ref> The two teams visited each other, with representatives from JAXA visiting the OSIRIS-REx Science Operations Center at the University of Arizona, and members of the OSIRIS-REx team traveling to Japan to meet with the Hayabusa2 team.<ref>{{cite web|title = Mission Update Apr. 22, 2019|date = 22 April 2019| url = https://www.asteroidmission.org/?mission_update=apr-22-2019| website = AsteroidMission.org| publisher = [[NASA]] | access-date = 12 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title =This week we're hosting Science Team Meeting 12 at @uarizona. More than 100 members of @nasa's OSIRIS-REx team and @jaxajp's Hayabusa2 team are gathered in Tucson to exchange information, share ideas and plan ways the two #asteroid-bound missions can collaborate. #science|website=Instagram|publisher = OSIRIS-REx |date = 29 March 2017|url = https://www.instagram.com/p/BSO5YjKBLwf/|access-date = 12 February 2020}}</ref> The teams are sharing software, data, and techniques for analysis, and will eventually exchange portions of the samples that are returned to Earth.<ref>{{cite web|title =Two Pieces of a Cosmic Puzzle: Hayabusa2 and OSIRIS-REx| first1= Christine |last1 = Hoekenga| date= 22 June 2018|website= AsteroidMission.org| publisher = [[NASA]]| url = https://www.asteroidmission.org/?latest-news=two-pieces-cosmic-puzzle-hayabusa2-osiris-rex | access-date = 12 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title = Collaboration Between OSIRIS-REx and Hayabusa2 | first1 = Dante | last1 = Lauretta| date = 20 October 2014| publisher = [[The Planetary Society]] | url = https://www.planetary.org/blogs/guest-blogs/dante-lauretta/20141020-collaboration-between.html | access-date = 12 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==OSIRIS-REx II==\nOSIRIS-REx II was a 2012 mission concept to replicate the original spacecraft for a double mission, with the second vehicle collecting samples from the two moons of Mars, [[Phobos (moon)|Phobos]] and [[Deimos (moon)|Deimos]]. It was stated that this mission would be both the quickest and least expensive way to get samples from the moons.<ref>{{cite conference |url=http://www.lpi.usra.edu/meetings/marsconcepts2012/pdf/4017.pdf |title=OSIRIS-REx II to Mars - Mars Sample Return from Phobos and Deimos |conference=Concepts and Approaches for Mars Exploration. 12\u201314 June 2012. Houston, Texas. |first=T. L. |last=Elifritz |date=2012 |bibcode=2012LPICo1679.4017E}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.extremetech.com/extreme/229171-osiris-rex-is-about-to-go-collect-and-return-samples-from-an-asteroid |title=OSIRIS-REx is about to go collect (and return) samples from an asteroid |work=ExtremeTech |first=Graham |last=Templeton |date=31 May 2016 |accessdate=24 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n{{multiple images |align=center |direction=horizontal |header=Views from OSIRIS REx |total_width = 1200\n|image1=NASA\u2019s_OSIRIS-REx_Captures_New_Earth-Moon_Image_(cropped).png |caption1=Earth-Moon system during an engineering test (January 2018).\n|image2=OSIRIS-REx_First_Image_of_Asteroid_Bennu.gif |caption2=First images of asteroid Bennu (August 2018).\n|image3=NASA-EarthMoonLowerLeft-BennuAsteroidUpperRight-20190108.jpg |caption3=Earth-Moon (lower left) and asteroid Bennu (upper right) (December 2018).<ref name=\"AP-20190108\">{{cite news |last=Dunn |first=Marcia |title=Asteroid-circling spacecraft grabs cool snapshot of home width2=200|url=https://apnews.com/de76da4abcc04c288109201c33e22a2c |date=8 January 2019 |work=[[AP News]] |accessdate=8 January 2019 }}</ref>\n|image4=OSIRIX-REx views Asteroid Bennu.jpg |caption4=Asteroid Bennu from {{convert|330|km|mi|abbr=on}} away (29 October 2018).\n|image5=OSIRIS-REx SRC and Bennu.png|caption5 = The Sample Return Capsule (SRC) with asteroid Bennu in the background (December 2019).\n|footer=\n}}\n\n==See also==\n\n* {{annotated link|Asteroidal water}}\n* {{annotated link|Hayabusa}}\n* {{annotated link|Hayabusa2}}\n* {{annotated link|List of asteroids visited by spacecraft}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|OSIRIS-REx}}\n* [http://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/osiris-rex/ OSIRIS-REx website] at NASA\n* [http://www.asteroidmission.org OSIRIS-REx website] at the University of Arizona\n* [https://pdssbn.astro.umd.edu/data_sb/missions/orex/index.shtml ''OSIRIS-REx'' Mission Archive] at the NASA Planetary Data System, Small Bodies Node\n\n{{Asteroid spacecraft}}\n{{Planetary Missions Program Office|New Frontiers=y}}\n{{Planetary defense}}\n{{Astrobiology}}\n{{Solar System probes}}\n{{Orbital launches in 2016}}\n{{2016 in space}}\n{{2018 in space}}\n{{2020 in space}}\n{{Portal bar|Astronomy|Space|Spaceflight}}\n\n[[Category:OSIRIS-REx| ]]\n[[Category:NASA space probes]]\n[[Category:Space probes launched in 2016]]\n[[Category:Missions to near-Earth asteroids]]\n[[Category:New Frontiers program]]\n[[Category:Astrobiology space missions]]\n[[Category:Planetary defense]]\n[[Category:Sample return missions]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched by Atlas rockets]]\n", "name_user": "Yarnalgo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSample acquisition", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.or