n the United States|Wealth in the United States}}\n{{See also|Personal income in the United States|Household income in the United States|Income inequality in the United States|Affluence in the United States|United States counties by per capita income}}\n[[File:U.S. Change in real income versus selected goods and services v1.png|thumb|left|U.S. Change in real income versus selected goods and services v1]]\n[[File:Realcompenstionusa.png|thumb|right|Real compensation per hour in the US.  Does not include non-cash compensation. (1947\u20132018).]]\n[[Image:US Real Wages 1964-2004.gif|thumb|Historical graph of [[real wages]] in the US from 1964 to 2005]]\n{{clear}}\n\n===Productivity===\n<blockquote>The share of national income going to employees is at approximately the same level now as it was in 1970.<ref>[http://www.nber.org/digest/oct08/w13953.html Total Compensation Reflects Growth in Productivity, ''National  Bureau of Economic Research'']</ref>  </blockquote>\n\n<blockquote>Much of the apparent divergence between pay and productivity stems from using different surveys and formulas to calculate inflation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.americanexperiment.org/2017/09/when-you-measure-it-properly-workers-compensation-is-driven-by-productivity/|title=When you measure it properly, worker's compensation is driven by productivity|date=September 19, 2017}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n===Inequality===\n{{Main|Income inequality in the United States|Poverty in the United States}}\n[[File:Top income inequality in the United States.png|thumb|left|Top income inequality in the United States and France]]\n[[File:Top 1% fiscal income share.png|thumb|right|Top 1% fiscal income share]]\n[[File:The US Gini Coefficient for Household Income (1967 - 2007 ).png|thumb|left|[[Gini Coefficient]] for Household Income (1967\u20132007), source [[United States Chamber of Commerce]]]]\n[[File:U.S. Income Shares of Top 1% and 0.1% 1913-2013.png|thumb|right|U.S. Income Shares of Top 1% and 0.1% 1913\u20