{"title_page": "Homer Hanky", "text_new": "{{short description|American handkerchief}}\n[[File:91hankycrop.jpg|thumb|A 1991 Homer Hanky]]\n\nThe '''Official [[Star Tribune]] [[Minnesota Twins]] Homer Hanky'''  is a [[handkerchief]] printed with a (usually red) [[baseball]]-shaped logo during Minnesota Twins championship seasons (and in 1988 after winning the World Series in 1987).  It was first introduced during the 1987 Pennant race, when the Twins won the [[American League]] Western division (AL West), by the'' ''Minneapolis ''Star Tribune'' as a promotional item for the newspaper during the pennant race.<ref>{{cite news | first=Ben | last=Tracy | coauthors= | authorlink= | title=Good Question: What Is The Homer Hanky's History? | date=Oct 4, 2006 | publisher=CBS Broadcasting Inc. | url=http://wcco.com/goodquestion/Good.Question.Homer.2.362040.html | work=WCCO | pages= | accessdate=2009-01-13 | language= | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081215175602/http://wcco.com/goodquestion/Good.Question.Homer.2.362040.html | archive-date=December 15, 2008 | url-status=dead }}</ref> The Homer Hanky is manufactured by the Winona, Minnesota based company, WinCraft Inc..<ref>{{cite web |title=Twins, Star Tribune and CUB partner for 2019 Homer Hanky |url=https://www.mlb.com/press-release/press-release-twins-star-tribune-cub-partner-homer-hanky |website=mlb.com |accessdate=17 April 2020 |date=October 9, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Twins' Homer Hanky a hit as fans root for pennant |url=https://www.postbulletin.com/twins-homer-hanky-a-hit-as-fans-root-for-pennant/article_874c3108-cc90-59a0-ad81-7d43e0dffb31.html |website=Post-Bulletin |accessdate=17 April 2020 |date=September 19, 1991}}</ref>\n{{TOC right}}\n\n==Years==\n\n===1987===\n{{main|1987 in baseball|1987 Minnesota Twins season}}\n* ''1987'': Red, baseball-shaped logo.\n** Printed at the end of the season\n** Created by Star Tribune promotions manager Terrie Robbins<ref>{{cite news | first= | last= | coauthors= | authorlink= | title=Good Question: What is the Homer Hanky's History? | date=Oct 4, 2006 | publisher=CBS Broadcasting | url=http://wcco.com/goodquestion/Good.Question.Homer.2.362040.html | work=WCCO.com | pages= | accessdate=2009-01-13 | language= | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081215175602/http://wcco.com/goodquestion/Good.Question.Homer.2.362040.html | archive-date=December 15, 2008 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n** Twins won [[1987 World Series|World Series]] (4\u20131 [[1987 American League Championship Series|ALCS]]def Detroit Tigers, 4\u20133 WS, def St. Louis Cardinals)<ref>{{cite news | first= | last= | coauthors= | authorlink= | title=Minnesota Twins Owner Carl Pohlad Dies At 93 | date=Jan 5, 2009 | publisher=Associated Press | url=http://wcco.com/sports/Carl.Pohlad.dies.2.900562.html | work=WCCO.com | pages= | accessdate=2009-01-13 | language= | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091221005538/http://wcco.com/sports/Carl.Pohlad.dies.2.900562.html | archive-date=December 21, 2009 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===1988===\n{{main|1988 in baseball|1988 Minnesota Twins season}}\n* ''1988'': Red, [[baseball diamond]]-shaped logo.\n** Printed at the beginning of the season\n** Twins finished 2nd in AL West behind the [[Oakland A's]]\n\n===1989\u20131990===\nGap between 1989 and 1990\n\n===1991\u20131992===\n{{main|1991 in baseball|1991 Minnesota Twins season}}\n* ''1991'': Red, baseball-shaped logo.\n** Printed at the end of the season\n** Twins won [[1991 World Series|World Series]] (4-1 [[1991 American League Championship Series|ALCS]] def Toronto Blue Jays, 4-3 WS, def Atlanta Braves)\n* ''1992'': Red, baseball-shaped logo.\n** Printed at the beginning of the season\n** Twins finished 2nd in AL West behind the Oakland A's\n\n===1993\u20132001===\nGap between 1993 and 2001\n\n===2002===\n{{main|2002 in baseball|2002 Minnesota Twins season}}\n* ''2002'': Red, baseball-shaped logo.\n** Printed at the end of the season\n** Twins won AL Central and [[2002 American League Division Series|AL Division Series]] (def. Oakland A's 3\u20132) but lost [[2002 American League Championship Series|AL Championship Series]] to [[Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim|Anaheim Angels]] (1\u20134).\nIn 2002 there seems to be two sizes of the Homer Hanky \"Proud and Loud\". A larger and \"normal\" size of 15{{fraction|1|2}} inch square and a smaller size of 13{{fraction|1|2}} inches square with \"hanky stitching\" on the edge.\n\n===2003===\n{{main|2003 in baseball|2003 Minnesota Twins season}}\n* ''2003'': Blue, baseball-shaped logo.\n** Printed at the end of the season\n** Twins won AL Central but lost [[2003 American League Division Series|AL Division Series]] to [[New York Yankees]] (1\u20133).\n\n===2004===\n{{main|2004 in baseball|2004 Minnesota Twins season}}\n[[File:2004 Minnesota Twins Homer Hanky.jpg|thumb|2004 Hanky]]\n* ''2004'': Red, outline of a baseball field\n** Printed at the end of the season\n** Twins won AL Central but lost [[2004 American League Division Series|AL Division Series]] to New York Yankees (1\u20133).\n\n===2004\u20132005===\nGap between 2004 and 2005\n\n===2006===\n{{main|2006 in baseball|2006 Minnesota Twins season}}\n* ''2006'': Red, State of MN with Minneapolis and St. Paul baseball player shaking hands (similar to the Twins logo from 1961 to 1986)\n* Twins won AL Central on the last day of the regular season, October 1, 2006\n* Twins lost in the [[2006 American League Division Series|ALDS]] to the [[Oakland Athletics]] (0\u20133)\n** Printed at the end of the season, available September 28, 2006\n\n===2007===\n* In 2007, the Minnesota Twins released a 20th anniversary Homer Hanky commemorating the 1987 World Series victory.\n\n===2008===\nGap in 2008\n\n===2009===\n* Homer Hankies were given to all fans during what was to be the last regular season game at the Metrodome on October 4, 2009.\n* On October 6, 2009, the ''Star Tribune'' and the Minnesota Twins announced that there would be a 2009 Homer Hanky available.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://minnesota.twins.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20091007&content_id=7385162&vkey=pr_min&fext=.jsp&c_id=min|title=AL Central Division Champion Minnesota Twins Announce the Homer Hanky is Back|work=Minnesota Twins}}</ref>\n* The Twins won AL Central after beating the Detroit Tigers in one game playoff to determine the division champion on October 6.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://minnesota.twins.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091007&content_id=7376368&vkey=news_min&fext=.jsp&c_id=min|title=Tiebreaker filled with intense drama|work=Minnesota Twins}}</ref>\n\n===2010===\n* Homer Hankies were given to all fans before the 2010 Home Opener at [[Target Field]]. These Hankies featured the official Target Field inaugural season logo and the words \"The Official Opening Day Homer Hanky\" across the top, and \"April 12th, 2010 Twins vs. Red Sox\" across the bottom.\n* On September 22, the Twins introduced a 2010 Championship Hanky.\n\n===2014===\n* Homer Hankies were released for All-Star Week on July 11th, 2014. These hankies featured a red Minnesota outline and \"All Star Week 2014\" in blue.\n\n===2019===\n\n* The Star Tribune announced, in celebration of the Twins winning the AL Central regular season division championship in 2019, that a new Homer Hanky would be released.  They noted that the new hanky will not be white, as in previous years. This was the result of Major League Baseball adding a new rule forbidding white [[rally towel]]s. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://startribune.com/the-homer-hanky-had-to-make-a-comeback-for-this-twins-team/561781232/|title=The Homer Hanky Had To Make A Comeback For This Twins Team|publisher=StarTribune.com}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Handy horn]]\n* [[Rally towel]]\n* [[Terrible Towel]]\n* [[Vuvuzela]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Minnesota Twins}}\n\n[[Category:Minnesota Twins]]\n[[Category:Sports paraphernalia]]\n[[Category:1987 introductions]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American handkerchief}}\n[[File:91hankycrop.jpg|thumb|A 1991 Homer Hanky]]\n\nThe '''Official [[Star Tribune]] [[Minnesota Twins]] Homer Hanky'''  is a [[handkerchief]] printed with a (usually red) [[baseball]]-shaped logo during Minnesota Twins championship seasons (and in 1988 after winning the World Series in 1987).  It was first introduced during the 1987 Pennant race, when the Twins won the [[American League]] Western division (AL West), by the'' ''Minneapolis ''Star Tribune'' as a promotional item for the newspaper during the pennant race.<ref>{{cite news | first=Ben | last=Tracy | coauthors= | authorlink= | title=Good Question: What Is The Homer Hanky's History? | date=Oct 4, 2006 | publisher=CBS Broadcasting Inc. | url=http://wcco.com/goodquestion/Good.Question.Homer.2.362040.html | work=WCCO | pages= | accessdate=2009-01-13 | language= | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081215175602/http://wcco.com/goodquestion/Good.Question.Homer.2.362040.html | archive-date=December 15, 2008 | url-status=dead }}</ref> The Homer Hanky is manufactured by the Minnesota based company, [[WinCraft Inc.]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Twins, Star Tribune and CUB partner for 2019 Homer Hanky |url=https://www.mlb.com/press-release/press-release-twins-star-tribune-cub-partner-homer-hanky |website=mlb.com |accessdate=17 April 2020 |date=October 9, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Twins' Homer Hanky a hit as fans root for pennant |url=https://www.postbulletin.com/twins-homer-hanky-a-hit-as-fans-root-for-pennant/article_874c3108-cc90-59a0-ad81-7d43e0dffb31.html |website=Post-Bulletin |accessdate=17 April 2020 |date=September 19, 1991}}</ref>\n{{TOC right}}\n\n==Years==\n\n===1987===\n{{main|1987 in baseball|1987 Minnesota Twins season}}\n* ''1987'': Red, baseball-shaped logo.\n** Printed at the end of the season\n** Created by Star Tribune promotions manager Terrie Robbins<ref>{{cite news | first= | last= | coauthors= | authorlink= | title=Good Question: What is the Homer Hanky's History? | date=Oct 4, 2006 | publisher=CBS Broadcasting | url=http://wcco.com/goodquestion/Good.Question.Homer.2.362040.html | work=WCCO.com | pages= | accessdate=2009-01-13 | language= | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081215175602/http://wcco.com/goodquestion/Good.Question.Homer.2.362040.html | archive-date=December 15, 2008 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n** Twins won [[1987 World Series|World Series]] (4\u20131 [[1987 American League Championship Series|ALCS]]def Detroit Tigers, 4\u20133 WS, def St. Louis Cardinals)<ref>{{cite news | first= | last= | coauthors= | authorlink= | title=Minnesota Twins Owner Carl Pohlad Dies At 93 | date=Jan 5, 2009 | publisher=Associated Press | url=http://wcco.com/sports/Carl.Pohlad.dies.2.900562.html | work=WCCO.com | pages= | accessdate=2009-01-13 | language= | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091221005538/http://wcco.com/sports/Carl.Pohlad.dies.2.900562.html | archive-date=December 21, 2009 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===1988===\n{{main|1988 in baseball|1988 Minnesota Twins season}}\n* ''1988'': Red, [[baseball diamond]]-shaped logo.\n** Printed at the beginning of the season\n** Twins finished 2nd in AL West behind the [[Oakland A's]]\n\n===1989\u20131990===\nGap between 1989 and 1990\n\n===1991\u20131992===\n{{main|1991 in baseball|1991 Minnesota Twins season}}\n* ''1991'': Red, baseball-shaped logo.\n** Printed at the end of the season\n** Twins won [[1991 World Series|World Series]] (4-1 [[1991 American League Championship Series|ALCS]] def Toronto Blue Jays, 4-3 WS, def Atlanta Braves)\n* ''1992'': Red, baseball-shaped logo.\n** Printed at the beginning of the season\n** Twins finished 2nd in AL West behind the Oakland A's\n\n===1993\u20132001===\nGap between 1993 and 2001\n\n===2002===\n{{main|2002 in baseball|2002 Minnesota Twins season}}\n* ''2002'': Red, baseball-shaped logo.\n** Printed at the end of the season\n** Twins won AL Central and [[2002 American League Division Series|AL Division Series]] (def. Oakland A's 3\u20132) but lost [[2002 American League Championship Series|AL Championship Series]] to [[Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim|Anaheim Angels]] (1\u20134).\nIn 2002 there seems to be two sizes of the Homer Hanky \"Proud and Loud\". A larger and \"normal\" size of 15{{fraction|1|2}} inch square and a smaller size of 13{{fraction|1|2}} inches square with \"hanky stitching\" on the edge.\n\n===2003===\n{{main|2003 in baseball|2003 Minnesota Twins season}}\n* ''2003'': Blue, baseball-shaped logo.\n** Printed at the end of the season\n** Twins won AL Central but lost [[2003 American League Division Series|AL Division Series]] to [[New York Yankees]] (1\u20133).\n\n===2004===\n{{main|2004 in baseball|2004 Minnesota Twins season}}\n[[File:2004 Minnesota Twins Homer Hanky.jpg|thumb|2004 Hanky]]\n* ''2004'': Red, outline of a baseball field\n** Printed at the end of the season\n** Twins won AL Central but lost [[2004 American League Division Series|AL Division Series]] to New York Yankees (1\u20133).\n\n===2004\u20132005===\nGap between 2004 and 2005\n\n===2006===\n{{main|2006 in baseball|2006 Minnesota Twins season}}\n* ''2006'': Red, State of MN with Minneapolis and St. Paul baseball player shaking hands (similar to the Twins logo from 1961 to 1986)\n* Twins won AL Central on the last day of the regular season, October 1, 2006\n* Twins lost in the [[2006 American League Division Series|ALDS]] to the [[Oakland Athletics]] (0\u20133)\n** Printed at the end of the season, available September 28, 2006\n\n===2007===\n* In 2007, the Minnesota Twins released a 20th anniversary Homer Hanky commemorating the 1987 World Series victory.\n\n===2008===\nGap in 2008\n\n===2009===\n* Homer Hankies were given to all fans during what was to be the last regular season game at the Metrodome on October 4, 2009.\n* On October 6, 2009, the ''Star Tribune'' and the Minnesota Twins announced that there would be a 2009 Homer Hanky available.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://minnesota.twins.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20091007&content_id=7385162&vkey=pr_min&fext=.jsp&c_id=min|title=AL Central Division Champion Minnesota Twins Announce the Homer Hanky is Back|work=Minnesota Twins}}</ref>\n* Twins won AL Central after beating the Detroit Tigers in one game playoff to determine the division champion on October 6.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://minnesota.twins.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091007&content_id=7376368&vkey=news_min&fext=.jsp&c_id=min|title=Tiebreaker filled with intense drama|work=Minnesota Twins}}</ref>\n\n===2010===\n* Homer Hankies were given to all fans before the 2010 Home Opener at [[Target Field]]. These Hankies featured the official Target Field inaugural season logo and the words \"The Official Opening Day Homer Hanky\" across the top, and \"April 12th, 2010 Twins vs. Red Sox\" across the bottom.\n* On September 22, the Twins introduced a 2010 Championship Hanky.\n\n===2014===\n* Homer Hankies were released for All-Star Week on July 11th, 2014. These hankies featured a red Minnesota outline and \"All Star Week 2014\" in blue.\n\n===2019===\n\n* The Star Tribune announced, in celebration of the Twins winning the AL Central regular season division championship in 2019, that a new Homer Hanky would be released.  They noted that the new hanky will not be white, as in previous years. This was the result of Major League Baseball adding a new rule forbidding white [[rally towel]]s. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://startribune.com/the-homer-hanky-had-to-make-a-comeback-for-this-twins-team/561781232/|title=The Homer Hanky Had To Make A Comeback For This Twins Team|publisher=StarTribune.com}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Handy horn]]\n* [[Rally towel]]\n* [[Terrible Towel]]\n* [[Vuvuzela]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Minnesota Twins}}\n\n[[Category:Minnesota Twins]]\n[[Category:Sports paraphernalia]]\n[[Category:1987 introductions]]\n", "name_user": "Bunganator", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homer_Hanky"}
{"title_page": "Joan E. Biren", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}'''Joan E. Biren''' or '''JEB''' (born July 13, 1944 in Washington, DC)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://searcharchives.library.gwu.edu/repositories/2/resources/197|title=Collection: Joan E. Biren photograph collection {{!}} GW Libraries Archival Collection Guides|website=searcharchives.library.gwu.edu|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>, is an internationally recognized documentary artist. Her photographic and film work has chronicled the lives of lesbian, gay, [[bisexual]], and [[transgender]] people for more than 30 years, bringing them a new visibility.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Summers|first1=Claude|title=The queer encyclopedia of the visual arts|date=2004|publisher=Cleis Press|location=San Francisco|isbn=}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\nJEB's films include ''No Secret Anymore: The Times of Del Martin and Phyllis Lyon''; ''Removing the Barriers'', used to train healthcare providers to improve service to lesbian clients; ''Women Organize!''; and ''Solidarity, Not Charity'' on relief efforts in New Orleans following Hurricane Katrina.<ref>{{cite web|title=Women Organize!|url=http://www.wmm.com/filmcatalog/pages/c536.shtml|publisher=Women Make Movies|accessdate=June 6, 2015}}</ref> Additional notable films have included ''Lesbian Physicians on Practice, Patients and Power'' and ''For Love and For Life: The 1987 March on Washington for Lesbian and Gay Rights.''<ref name=rhp_biren>{{cite web|title=Community Pioneers: Joan E. Biren|url=http://rainbowhistory.omeka.net/exhibits/show/pioneers/2007awardees/jeb|publisher=Rainbow History Project|accessdate=June 5, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304043915/http://rainbowhistory.omeka.net/exhibits/show/pioneers/2007awardees/jeb|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> The first film is still commonly screened in medical schools around the country and the latter has been broadcast on public television.\n\nBiren produced and wrote ''A Simple Matter of Justice,'' which documented the 1993 March on Washington for Lesbian, Gay, and Bi Equal Rights and Liberation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.frameline.org/distribution/distribution-catalog/distribution-film-index/a-simple-matter-of-justice-the-1993-march-on-washington-for-lesbian-gay-and-bi-equal-rights-and-liberation|title=A Simple Matter of Justice: The 1993 March on Washington for Lesbian, Gay and Bi Equal Rights and Liberation|website=www.frameline.org|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>  The one-hour film received wide acclaim and was voted \"Best Video\" at the Washington, DC Reel Affirmations Film Festival.  To produce this piece, Joan set up a live six-camera switch feed that simultaneously broadcast footage on jumbo screens located on the National Mall and around the world.<ref name=\"Guide to the Joan E. Biren Photograph Collection, 1971-1991\">[http://library.gwu.edu/ead/ms2019.xml Guide to the Joan E. Biren Photograph Collection, 1971\u20131991] Special Collections Research Center, Estelle and Melvin Gelman Library, The George Washington University</ref>\n\n==Early career: The Furies and photography==\nJoan attended [[Mt. Holyoke College]] in South Hadley, Massachusetts, where she received her B.A. in political science.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020|reason=Citation to RS required}}  She later received a M.A. in Communication at [[American University]] in Washington, D.C.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020|reason=Citation to RS required}}   After three years of pursuing doctoral studies at [[Oxford University]], Biren returned home to America.  While working at a camera store and small town newspaper, Biren began to teach herself photography skills that laid the foundation for her future career.\n\nIn her early 20s, Biren and others, including [[Rita Mae Brown]] and [[Charlotte Bunch]], formed the [[Furies Collective]], a radical experiment in [[lesbian separatist|lesbian feminist separatist]] organizing. Though the collective lasted only about 18 months, it had a profound influence on lesbian thought through its newspaper, ''The Furies'', and other publications.<ref name=rhp_biren /><ref name=jeb_fivecollege>{{cite web|title=Finding Aid to the Joan E. Biren Papers, 1944\u20132011|url=http://asteria.fivecolleges.edu/findaids/sophiasmith/mnsss511.html|publisher=Five College Archive and Manuscripts Collections|accessdate=November 24, 2012}}</ref> \n\nIt was in the collective that JEB began developing her skills in photography. As she has stated, \"I needed to see images of lesbians.\"<ref name=jeb_fivecollege /> Her books ''Eye to Eye: Portraits of Lesbians'' (1979) and ''Making a Way: Lesbians Out Front'' (1987) brought groundbreaking visibility to lesbian lives.<ref name=\"pitman\">{{citation |last=Pitman |first=Gayle |chapter=JEB (Joan E. Biren): Lesbian Photographer, Video Producer, activist |title=Everyday Mutinies: Funding Lesbian Activism |pages=[https://archive.org/details/everydaymutinies00gart/page/23 23\u201332] |editor-first=Nanette |editor-last=Gartrell |editor2-first=Esther D |editor2-last=Rothblum |year=2001 |publisher=Haworth Press |isbn=1-56023-259-5 |url=https://archive.org/details/everydaymutinies00gart/page/23 }}</ref> In 1997, [[George Washington University]] mounted a retrospective exhibit of JEB's work, ''Queerly Visible: 1971\u20131991'', which later toured the nation.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020|reason=Citation to RS required}} \nIn 2011, [[Leslie-Lohman Museum of Gay and Lesbian Art]] held a retrospective show, \"Lesbians Seeing Lesbians: Building Community in Early Feminist Photography\".<ref>{{cite web|title=LESBIANS SEEING LESBIANS: Building Community in Early Feminist Photography|url=http://www.leslielohman.org/exhibitions/2011/lesbians-seeing-lesbians.html|publisher=Leslie-Lohman Museum of Gay and Lesbian Art|accessdate=June 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\nHer mentors included [[Audre Lorde]] and [[Barbara Deming]]. She said, \"I watched them, and I read what they wrote, and I translated it into visuals that I needed to share as widely as possible.\"{{Citation needed|date=April 2020|reason=Citation to RS required}}  In her photography, Joan tried to break away from the traditional power structures associated with photography. She preferred to use the term \"muse\" rather than \"subject.\" She would also try to interact with her \"muses\" on equal terns. If she was photographing a nude woman, she would ask if the women wanted her to be nude as well.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/08/lens/lesbian-lives-movement-jeb.html|title=Photos of Lesbian Lives Meant to Inspire a Movement|last=Manders|first=Kerry|date=April 8, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=9 April 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn an effort to ensure that affirming images and positive self-expression occurred outside of what she considered traditional patriarchal venues, Biren included her work in ''[[off our backs]]'', The ''[[Washington Blade]]'', ''[[Gay Community News (Boston)|Gay Community News]]'', and on many LP album and book covers.<ref name=jeb_fivecollege />\n==Career==\nFor many years, JEB traveled the country presenting her multi-projector slideshows and running photography workshops. In the early 1990s, she moved from slideshows to film making. JEB's award-winning films have been seen on the [[Sundance Channel (United States)|Sundance Channel]] and public broadcasting stations. She is the president of Moonforce Media, a non-profit company, which produces and distributes films and videos that challenge people to work for social justice and awards The [[Tee Corinne|Tee A. Corinne]] Prize, an annual grant to lesbian media makers.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020|reason=Citation to RS required}} \n\nJEB's papers and visual materials will be permanently archived at The [[Sophia Smith Collection]], the premiere women's history collection, at [[Smith College]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Power of Women Voices. Joan Biren (JEB)|url=http://www.smith.edu/libraries/libs/ssc/pwv/pwv-jeb.html|website=Smith College Libraries|publisher=Sophia Smith Collection, Smith College|accessdate=June 6, 2015}}</ref> Many of her photographs are located at the [[Library of Congress]] in Washington, D.C. In addition, The [[George Washington University]] houses a collection of photographs used in ''Queerly Visible: 1971\u20131991''.\n\nFrom Joan Biren's oral history in the Rainbow History Project collection:\n\n{{quote|... My thing was to take pictures of the people that other people weren't taking pictures of, to make visible what was invisible ... I always try to present the entire diversity of our community. That's always very much in my mind in all of my work.\n\nThe thing about the Furies is that, for as short a time as we existed, we had a big impact. The ideology was very influential....</blockquote>\n\nIn 1995, Biren became an associate of the [[Women's Institute for Freedom of the Press]] (WIFP).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wifp.org/who-we-are/associates/|title=Associates {{!}}  The Women's Institute for Freedom of the Press|website=www.wifp.org|access-date=21 June 2017}}</ref> WIFP is an American nonprofit publishing organization. The organization works to increase communication between women and connect the public with forms of women-based media.\n\n==Bibliography of works by Joan E. Biren==\n\n*{{cite book|last=Biren|first=Joan E.|title=Eye to eye : portraits of lesbians : photographs / by JEB ; with a foreword by Joan Nestle, and an introd. by Judith Schwarz.|year=1979|publisher=Glad Hag Books ; [Weatherby Lake, MO : distributed by Naiad Press]|location=Washington, D.C.|isbn=0960317600|pages=[https://archive.org/details/eyetoeyeportrait00jebe/page/72 72]|url=https://archive.org/details/eyetoeyeportrait00jebe/page/72}}\n*{{cite book|last=Biren|first=Joan E.|title=Making a way : lesbians out front / photographs by JEB (Joan E. Biren) ; foreword by Minnie Bruce Pratt.|year=1987|publisher=Glad Hag Books ; San Francisco, CA : Distributed by Spinsters/Aunt Lute|location=Washington, D.C.|isbn=0960317619|pages=112|author2=Minnie Bruce Pratt}}\n*{{cite book|last=Deming|first=Barbra|title=Prisons that could not hold / Barbara Deming ; introduction by Grace Paley ; photo essay edited by Joan E. Biren.|year=c. 1985|publisher=Spinsters Ink|location=San Francisco|isbn=0933216157|pages=[https://archive.org/details/prisonsthatcould00demi/page/230 230]|author2=Joan E. Biren|type=paperback|url=https://archive.org/details/prisonsthatcould00demi/page/230}}\n*{{cite book |title=Queerly visible, 1971-1991 : the work of JEB (Joan E. Biren) : an exhibition in the GW Gelman Library, September 4 through November 21, 1997.|year=c. 1997|publisher=Special Collections Department, the Gelman Library, the George Washington University|location=[Washington]}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n===Archival resources===\n*[http://asteria.fivecolleges.edu/findaids/sophiasmith/mnsss511.html Joan E. Biren Papers, 1944\u20132011] (circa 70 linear feet) are housed at the [[Five College Archives and Manuscript Collections]].\n*[http://library.gwu.edu/ead/ms2019.xml Guide to the Joan E. Biren Photograph Collection, 1971\u20131991, Special Collections Research Center, Estelle and Melvin Gelman Library, The George Washington University]\n*[http://library.gwu.edu/ead/ms2156.xml Guide to the Tacie Dejanikus Papers, 1967\u20131992, Special Collections Research Center, Estelle and Melvin Gelman Library, The George Washington University]\n\n==External links==\n{{external media\n|video1= [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=97Rp4L4XyUs \"No Secret Anymore: The Times of Del Martin and Phyllis Lyon\"], trailer\n|video2= [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3MbWNfX5NT8 \"A Simple Matter of Justice: The 1993 March on Washington for Lesbian, Gay and Bi Equal Rights and Liberation\"], trailer\n|video3= [https://vimeo.com/36395393 \"Lesbians Seeing Lesbians.\"] Artist & Curator panel. The Leslie-Lohman Museum of Gay & Lesbian Art. \n}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080620123146/http://jebmedia.com/index.html Official site]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160305033332/http://exhibits.library.gwu.edu/pdf/exhibit-queerly-visible.pdf Queerly Visible: The Work of J.E.B.], The George Washington University\n*[http://library.gwu.edu/ead/ms2019.xml Guide to the Joan E. Biren Photograph Collection, 1971\u20131991, Special Collections Research Center, Estelle and Melvin Gelman Library, The George Washington University]\n*Joan E. Biren. [http://media.smith.edu/departments/ssc/biren/biren-slideshow.html \"Look To the Women for Courage: Stories From the Seneca Encampment for Peace and Justice\"] (1984), [[Sophia Smith Collection]], [[Smith College]]\n*[http://www.smith.edu/libraries/libs/ssc/pwv/pwv-jeb.html \"The Power of Women's Voices\"], selections from [http://www.smith.edu/libraries/libs/ssc/vof/vof-intro.html Voices of Feminism Oral History Project], [[Sophia Smith Collection]], [[Smith College]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Biren, Joan E.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:American photographers]]\n[[Category:American women photographers]]\n[[Category:American documentary film directors]]\n[[Category:Feminist artists]]\n[[Category:Lesbian artists]]\n[[Category:Lesbian feminists]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT artists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Women documentary filmmakers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n'''Joan E. Biren''' or '''JEB''' (born 1944 in Washington, DC), is an internationally recognized documentary artist. Her photographic and film work has chronicled the lives of lesbian, gay, [[bisexual]], and [[transgender]] people for more than 30 years, bringing them a new visibility.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Summers|first1=Claude|title=The queer encyclopedia of the visual arts|date=2004|publisher=Cleis Press|location=San Francisco|isbn=}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\nJEB's films include ''No Secret Anymore: The Times of Del Martin and Phyllis Lyon''; ''Removing the Barriers'', used to train healthcare providers to improve service to lesbian clients; ''Women Organize!''; and ''Solidarity, Not Charity'' on relief efforts in New Orleans following Hurricane Katrina.<ref>{{cite web|title=Women Organize!|url=http://www.wmm.com/filmcatalog/pages/c536.shtml|publisher=Women Make Movies|accessdate=June 6, 2015}}</ref> Additional notable films have included ''Lesbian Physicians on Practice, Patients and Power'' and ''For Love and For Life: The 1987 March on Washington for Lesbian and Gay Rights.''<ref name=rhp_biren>{{cite web|title=Community Pioneers: Joan E. Biren|url=http://rainbowhistory.omeka.net/exhibits/show/pioneers/2007awardees/jeb|publisher=Rainbow History Project|accessdate=June 5, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304043915/http://rainbowhistory.omeka.net/exhibits/show/pioneers/2007awardees/jeb|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> The first film is still commonly screened in medical schools around the country and the latter has been broadcast on public television.\n\nBiren produced and wrote ''A Simple Matter of Justice,'' which documented the 1993 March on Washington for Lesbian, Gay, and Bi Equal Rights and Liberation.  The one-hour film received wide acclaim and was voted \"Best Video\" at the Washington, DC Reel Affirmations Film Festival.  To produce this piece, Joan set up a live six-camera switch feed that simultaneously broadcast footage on jumbo screens located on the National Mall and around the world.<ref name=\"Guide to the Joan E. Biren Photograph Collection, 1971-1991\">[http://library.gwu.edu/ead/ms2019.xml Guide to the Joan E. Biren Photograph Collection, 1971\u20131991] Special Collections Research Center, Estelle and Melvin Gelman Library, The George Washington University</ref>\n\n==Early career: The Furies and photography==\nJoan attended [[Mt. Holyoke College]] in South Hadley, Massachusetts, where she received her B.A. in political science.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020|reason=Citation to RS required}}  She later received a M.A. in Communication at [[American University]] in Washington, D.C.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020|reason=Citation to RS required}}   After three years of pursuing doctoral studies at [[Oxford University]], Biren returned home to America.  While working at a camera store and small town newspaper, Biren began to teach herself photography skills that laid the foundation for her future career.\n\nIn her early 20s, Biren and others, including [[Rita Mae Brown]] and [[Charlotte Bunch]], formed the [[Furies Collective]], a radical experiment in [[lesbian separatist|lesbian feminist separatist]] organizing. Though the collective lasted only about 18 months, it had a profound influence on lesbian thought through its newspaper, ''The Furies'', and other publications.<ref name=rhp_biren /><ref name=jeb_fivecollege>{{cite web|title=Finding Aid to the Joan E. Biren Papers, 1944\u20132011|url=http://asteria.fivecolleges.edu/findaids/sophiasmith/mnsss511.html|publisher=Five College Archive and Manuscripts Collections|accessdate=November 24, 2012}}</ref> \n\nIt was in the collective that JEB began developing her skills in photography. As she has stated, \"I needed to see images of lesbians.\"<ref name=jeb_fivecollege /> Her books ''Eye to Eye: Portraits of Lesbians'' (1979) and ''Making a Way: Lesbians Out Front'' (1987) brought groundbreaking visibility to lesbian lives.<ref name=\"pitman\">{{citation |last=Pitman |first=Gayle |chapter=JEB (Joan E. Biren): Lesbian Photographer, Video Producer, activist |title=Everyday Mutinies: Funding Lesbian Activism |pages=[https://archive.org/details/everydaymutinies00gart/page/23 23\u201332] |editor-first=Nanette |editor-last=Gartrell |editor2-first=Esther D |editor2-last=Rothblum |year=2001 |publisher=Haworth Press |isbn=1-56023-259-5 |url=https://archive.org/details/everydaymutinies00gart/page/23 }}</ref> In 1997, [[George Washington University]] mounted a retrospective exhibit of JEB's work, ''Queerly Visible: 1971\u20131991'', which later toured the nation.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020|reason=Citation to RS required}} \nIn 2011, [[Leslie-Lohman Museum of Gay and Lesbian Art]] held a retrospective show, \"Lesbians Seeing Lesbians: Building Community in Early Feminist Photography\".<ref>{{cite web|title=LESBIANS SEEING LESBIANS: Building Community in Early Feminist Photography|url=http://www.leslielohman.org/exhibitions/2011/lesbians-seeing-lesbians.html|publisher=Leslie-Lohman Museum of Gay and Lesbian Art|accessdate=June 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\nHer mentors included [[Audre Lorde]] and [[Barbara Deming]]. She said, \"I watched them, and I read what they wrote, and I translated it into visuals that I needed to share as widely as possible.\"{{Citation needed|date=April 2020|reason=Citation to RS required}}  In her photography, Joan tried to break away from the traditional power structures associated with photography. She preferred to use the term \"muse\" rather than \"subject.\" She would also try to interact with her \"muses\" on equal terns. If she was photographing a nude woman, she would ask if the women wanted her to be nude as well.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/08/lens/lesbian-lives-movement-jeb.html|title=Photos of Lesbian Lives Meant to Inspire a Movement|last=Manders|first=Kerry|date=April 8, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=9 April 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn an effort to ensure that affirming images and positive self-expression occurred outside of what she considered traditional patriarchal venues, Biren included her work in ''[[off our backs]]'', The ''[[Washington Blade]]'', ''[[Gay Community News (Boston)|Gay Community News]]'', and on countless LP album and book covers.<ref name=jeb_fivecollege />\n\n\n==Career==\nFor many years, JEB traveled the country presenting her multi-projector slideshows and running photography workshops. In the early 1990s, she moved from slideshows to film making. JEB's award-winning films have been seen on the [[Sundance Channel (United States)|Sundance Channel]] and public broadcasting stations. She is the president of Moonforce Media, a non-profit company, which produces and distributes films and videos that challenge people to work for social justice and awards The [[Tee Corinne|Tee A. Corinne]] Prize, an annual grant to lesbian media makers.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020|reason=Citation to RS required}} \n\nJEB's papers and visual materials will be permanently archived at The [[Sophia Smith Collection]], the premiere women's history collection, at [[Smith College]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Power of Women Voices. Joan Biren (JEB)|url=http://www.smith.edu/libraries/libs/ssc/pwv/pwv-jeb.html|website=Smith College Libraries|publisher=Sophia Smith Collection, Smith College|accessdate=June 6, 2015}}</ref> Many of her photographs are located at the [[Library of Congress]] in Washington, D.C. In addition, The [[George Washington University]] houses a collection of photographs used in ''Queerly Visible: 1971\u20131991''.\n\nFrom Joan Biren's oral history in the Rainbow History Project collection:\n\n{{quote|... My thing was to take pictures of the people that other people weren't taking pictures of, to make visible what was invisible ... I always try to present the entire diversity of our community. That's always very much in my mind in all of my work.\n\nThe thing about the Furies is that, for as short a time as we existed, we had a big impact. The ideology was very influential....</blockquote>\n\nIn 1995, Biren became an associate of the [[Women's Institute for Freedom of the Press]] (WIFP).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wifp.org/who-we-are/associates/|title=Associates {{!}}  The Women's Institute for Freedom of the Press|website=www.wifp.org|access-date=21 June 2017}}</ref> WIFP is an American nonprofit publishing organization. The organization works to increase communication between women and connect the public with forms of women-based media.\n\n==Bibliography of works by Joan E. Biren==\n\n*{{cite book|last=Biren|first=Joan E.|title=Eye to eye : portraits of lesbians : photographs / by JEB ; with a foreword by Joan Nestle, and an introd. by Judith Schwarz.|year=1979|publisher=Glad Hag Books ; [Weatherby Lake, MO : distributed by Naiad Press]|location=Washington, D.C.|isbn=0960317600|pages=[https://archive.org/details/eyetoeyeportrait00jebe/page/72 72]|url=https://archive.org/details/eyetoeyeportrait00jebe/page/72}}\n*{{cite book|last=Biren|first=Joan E.|title=Making a way : lesbians out front / photographs by JEB (Joan E. Biren) ; foreword by Minnie Bruce Pratt.|year=1987|publisher=Glad Hag Books ; San Francisco, CA : Distributed by Spinsters/Aunt Lute|location=Washington, D.C.|isbn=0960317619|pages=112|author2=Minnie Bruce Pratt}}\n*{{cite book|last=Deming|first=Barbra|title=Prisons that could not hold / Barbara Deming ; introduction by Grace Paley ; photo essay edited by Joan E. Biren.|year=c. 1985|publisher=Spinsters Ink|location=San Francisco|isbn=0933216157|pages=[https://archive.org/details/prisonsthatcould00demi/page/230 230]|author2=Joan E. Biren|type=paperback|url=https://archive.org/details/prisonsthatcould00demi/page/230}}\n*{{cite book |title=Queerly visible, 1971-1991 : the work of JEB (Joan E. Biren) : an exhibition in the GW Gelman Library, September 4 through November 21, 1997.|year=c. 1997|publisher=Special Collections Department, the Gelman Library, the George Washington University|location=[Washington]}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n===Archival resources===\n*[http://asteria.fivecolleges.edu/findaids/sophiasmith/mnsss511.html Joan E. Biren Papers, 1944\u20132011] (circa 70 linear feet) are housed at the [[Five College Archives and Manuscript Collections]].\n*[http://library.gwu.edu/ead/ms2019.xml Guide to the Joan E. Biren Photograph Collecti